# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: laser-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] A **laser diode** (**LD**, also **injection laser diode** or **ILD** or **semiconductor laser** or **diode laser**) is a semiconductor device similar to a light-emitting diode in which a diode pumped directly with electrical current can create lasing conditions at the diode's junction.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Driven by voltage, the doped p–n-transition allows for recombination of an electron with a hole.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Due to the drop of the electron from a higher energy level to a lower one, radiation is generated in the form of an emitted photon.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Stimulated emission can be produced when the process is continued and further generates light with the same phase, coherence, and wavelength.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The choice of the semiconductor material determines the wavelength of the emitted beam, which in today's laser diodes range from the infrared (IR) to the ultraviolet (UV) spectra.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Laser diodes are the most common type of lasers produced, with a wide range of uses that include fiber-optic communications, barcode readers, laser pointers, CD/DVD/Blu-ray disc reading/recording, laser printing, laser scanning, and light beam illumination.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] With the use of a phosphor like that found on white LEDs, laser diodes can be used for general illumination.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] A laser diode is electrically a PIN diode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The active region of the laser diode is in the intrinsic (I) region, and the carriers (electrons and holes) are pumped into that region from the N and P regions respectively.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] While initial diode laser research was conducted on simple P–N diodes, all modern lasers use the double-hetero-structure implementation, where the carriers and the photons are confined in order to maximize their chances for recombination and light generation.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Unlike a regular diode, the goal for a laser diode is to recombine all carriers in the I region, and produce light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Thus, laser diodes are fabricated using direct band-gap semiconductors.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The laser diode epitaxial structure is grown using one of the crystal growth techniques, usually starting from an N-doped substrate, and growing the I (undoped) active layer, followed by the P-doped cladding, and a contact layer.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The active layer most often consists of quantum wells, which provide lower threshold current and higher efficiency.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Laser diodes form a subset of the larger classification of semiconductor *p*–*n* junction diodes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Forward electrical bias across the laser diode causes the two species of charge carrier – holes and electrons – to be *injected* from opposite sides of the PIN junction into the depletion region.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Holes are injected from the *p*-doped into the undoped (i) semiconductor, and electrons vice versa.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] As diode lasers are semiconductor devices, they may also be classified as semiconductor lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Either designation distinguishes diode lasers from solid-state lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Another method of powering some diode lasers is the use of optical pumping.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Optically pumped semiconductor lasers (OPSL) use a III-V semiconductor chip as the gain medium, and another laser (often another diode laser) as the pump source.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] OPSLs offer several advantages over ILDs, particularly in wavelength selection and lack of interference from internal electrode structures.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] A further advantage of OPSLs is invariance of the beam parameters – divergence, shape, and pointing – as pump power (and hence output power) is varied, even over a 10:1 output power ratio.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] (In a conventional semiconductor junction diode, the energy released from the recombination of electrons and holes is carried away as phonons (lattice vibrations) rather than as photons.) Spontaneous emission below the lasing threshold produces similar properties to an LED.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Spontaneous emission is necessary to initiate laser oscillation, but it is one among several sources of inefficiency once the laser is oscillating.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The difference between the photon-emitting semiconductor laser and a conventional phonon-emitting (non-light-emitting) semiconductor junction diode lies in the type of semiconductor used, one whose physical and atomic structure confers the possibility for photon emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] These photon-emitting semiconductors are the so-called "direct bandgap" semiconductors.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The properties of silicon and germanium, which are single-element semiconductors, have bandgaps that do not align in the way needed to allow photon emission and are not considered *direct*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Other materials, the so-called compound semiconductors, have virtually identical crystalline structures as silicon or germanium but use alternating arrangements of two different atomic species in a checkerboard-like pattern to break the symmetry.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The transition between the materials in the alternating pattern creates the critical direct bandgap property.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Gallium arsenide, indium phosphide, gallium antimonide, and gallium nitride are all examples of compound semiconductor materials that can be used to create junction diodes that emit light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] A nearby photon with energy equal to the recombination energy can cause recombination by stimulated emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This generates another photon of the same frequency, polarization, and phase, travelling in the same direction as the first photon.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This means that stimulated emission will cause gain in an optical wave (of the correct wavelength) in the injection region, and the gain increases as the number of electrons and holes injected across the junction increases.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The spontaneous and stimulated-emission processes are vastly more efficient in direct bandgap semiconductors than in indirect bandgap semiconductors; therefore, silicon is not a common material for laser diodes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] As in other lasers, the gain region is surrounded by an optical cavity to form a laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In the simplest form of laser diode, an optical waveguide is made on that crystal's surface, such that the light is confined to a relatively narrow line.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The two ends of the crystal are cleaved to form perfectly smooth, parallel edges, forming a Fabry–Pérot resonator.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Photons emitted into a mode of the waveguide will travel along the waveguide and be reflected several times from each end face before they exit.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] As a light wave passes through the cavity, it is amplified by stimulated emission, but light is also lost due to absorption and by incomplete reflection from the end facets.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Finally, if there is more amplification than loss, the diode begins to *lase*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Some important properties of laser diodes are determined by the geometry of the optical cavity.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Generally, the light is contained within a very thin layer, and the structure supports only a single optical mode in the direction perpendicular to the layers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In the transverse direction, if the waveguide is wide compared to the wavelength of the light, then the waveguide can support multiple transverse optical modes, and the laser is known as *multi-mode*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] These transversely multi-mode lasers are adequate in cases where one needs a very large amount of power, but not a small diffraction-limited TEM00 beam, such as in printing, activating chemicals, microscopy, or pumping other types of lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In applications where a small, focused beam is needed, the waveguide must be made narrow, on the order of the optical wavelength.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This way, only a single transverse mode is supported and one ends up with a diffraction-limited beam.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Such single-spatial-mode devices are used for optical storage, laser pointers, and fiber optics.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] These lasers may still support multiple longitudinal modes, and thus can lase at multiple wavelengths simultaneously.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The wavelength emitted is a function of the bandgap of the semiconductor material and the modes of the optical cavity.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In general, the maximum gain will occur for photons with energy slightly above the bandgap energy, and the modes nearest the peak of the gain curve will lase most strongly.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The width of the gain curve will determine the number of additional *side modes* that may also lase, depending on the operating conditions.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Single-spatial-mode lasers that can support multiple longitudinal modes are called Fabry-Pérot (FP) lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] An FP laser will lase at multiple cavity modes within the gain bandwidth of the lasing medium.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The number of lasing modes in an FP laser is usually unstable and can fluctuate due to changes in current or temperature.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Single-spatial-mode diode lasers can be designed so as to operate on a single longitudinal mode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] These single-frequency diode lasers exhibit a high degree of stability, and are used in spectroscopy and metrology and as frequency references.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Single-frequency diode lasers are classed as either distributed-feedback (DFB) lasers or distributed Bragg reflector (DBR) lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Due to diffraction, the beam diverges (expands) rapidly after leaving the chip, typically at 30 degrees vertically by 10 degrees laterally.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] A lens must be used in order to form a collimated beam like that produced by a laser pointer.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] If a circular beam is required, then cylindrical lenses and other optics are used.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] For single-spatial-mode lasers, using symmetrical lenses, the collimated beam ends up being elliptical in shape, due to the difference in the vertical and lateral divergences.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This is easily observable with a red laser pointer.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The long axis of the ellipse is at right-angles to the plane of the chip.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The simple diode described above has been heavily modified in recent years to accommodate modern technology, resulting in a variety of types of laser diodes, as described below.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Following theoretical treatments of M.G.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Dumke in the early 1960s, coherent light emission from a gallium arsenide (GaAs) semiconductor diode (a laser diode) was demonstrated in 1962 by two US groups led by Robert N.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Hall at the General Electric research center and by Marshall Nathan at the IBM T.J.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] There has been ongoing debate as to whether IBM or GE invented the first laser diode, which was largely based on theoretical work by William P.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Dumke at IBM's Kitchawan Lab (currently known as the Thomas J.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Watson Research Center) in Yorktown Heights, NY.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The priority is given to the General Electric group, who submitted their results earlier; they also went further and made a resonant cavity for their diode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] It was initially speculated, by MIT's Ben Lax among other leading physicists, that silicon or germanium could be used to create a lasing effect, but theoretical analyses convinced William P.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Dumke that these materials would not work.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Instead, he suggested gallium arsenide as a good candidate.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The first visible-wavelength laser diode was demonstrated by Nick Holonyak, Jr. later in 1962; he used gallium arsenide phosphide.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Other teams at MIT Lincoln Laboratory, Texas Instruments, and RCA Laboratories were also involved in, and received credit for, their historic initial demonstrations of efficient light emission and lasing in semiconductor diodes in 1962 and thereafter.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] GaAs lasers were also produced in early 1963 in the Soviet Union by the team led by Nikolay Basov.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In the early 1960s, liquid-phase epitaxy (LPE) was invented by Herbert Nelson of RCA Laboratories.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] By layering the highest-quality crystals of varying compositions, it enabled the demonstration of the highest-quality heterojunction semiconductor laser materials for many years.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] LPE was adopted by all the leading laboratories worldwide and was used for many years.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] It was finally supplanted in the 1970s by molecular-beam epitaxy and organometallic chemical vapor deposition.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Diode lasers of that era operated with threshold current densities of 1000 A/cm2 at 77 K temperatures.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Such performance enabled continuous lasing to be demonstrated in the earliest days.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] However, when operated at room temperature, about 300 K, threshold current densities were two orders of magnitude greater, or 100,000 A/cm2, in the best devices.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The dominant challenge for the remainder of the 1960s was to obtain low threshold current density at 300 K and thereby to demonstrate continuous-wave lasing at room temperature from a diode laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The first diode lasers were homojunction diodes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] That is, the material (and thus the bandgap) of the waveguide core layer and that of the surrounding clad layers were identical.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] It was recognized that there was an opportunity, particularly afforded by the use of liquid-phase epitaxy using aluminum gallium arsenide, to introduce heterojunctions.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Heterostructures consist of layers of semiconductor crystal having varying bandgap and refractive index.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Heterojunctions (formed from heterostructures) had been recognized by Herbert Kroemer, while working at RCA Laboratories in the mid-1950s, as having unique advantages for several types of electronic and optoelectronic devices, including diode lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] LPE afforded the technology of making heterojunction diode lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In 1963, he proposed the double heterostructure laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The first heterojunction diode lasers were single-heterojunction lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] These lasers used aluminum gallium arsenide *p*-type injectors situated over *n*-type gallium arsenide layers grown on the substrate by LPE.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] An admixture of aluminum replaced gallium in the semiconductor crystal and raised the bandgap of the *p*-type injector over that of the *n*-type layers beneath.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] It worked; the 300 K threshold currents went down by 10× to 10,000 A/cm2.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Unfortunately, this was still not in the needed range, and these single-heterostructure diode lasers did not function in continuous-wave operation at room temperature.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The innovation that met the room temperature challenge was the double-heterostructure laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The trick was to quickly move the wafer in the LPE apparatus between different *melts* of aluminum gallium arsenide (*p*- and *n*-type) and a third melt of gallium arsenide.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] It had to be done rapidly since the gallium arsenide core region needed to be significantly under 1 μm in thickness.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The first laser diode to achieve *continuous-wave* operation was a double heterostructure demonstrated in 1970 essentially simultaneously by Zhores Alferov and collaborators (including Dmitri Z.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Garbuzov) of the Soviet Union, and Morton Panish and Izuo Hayashi working in the United States.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] However, it is widely accepted that Alferov and team reached the milestone first.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] For their accomplishment and that of their co-workers, Alferov and Kroemer shared the 2000 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The simple laser diode structure described above is inefficient.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Such devices require so much power that they can only achieve pulsed operation without damage.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Although historically important and easy to explain, such devices are not practical.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In these devices, a layer of low-bandgap material is sandwiched between two high-bandgap layers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] One commonly used pair of materials is gallium arsenide (GaAs) with aluminium gallium arsenide (AlxGa(1-x)As).
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Each of the junctions between different bandgap materials is called a *heterostructure*, hence the name *double heterostructure* (DH) laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The kind of laser diode described in the first part of the article may be referred to as a *homojunction* laser, for contrast with these more popular devices.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The advantage of a DH laser is that the region where free electrons and holes exist simultaneously—the active region—is confined to the thin middle layer.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This means that many more of the electron-hole pairs can contribute to amplification—not so many are left out in the poorly amplifying periphery.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In addition, light is reflected within the heterojunction; hence, the light is confined to the region where the amplification takes place.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] If the middle layer is made thin enough, it acts as a quantum well.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This means that the vertical variation of the electron's wavefunction, and thus a component of its energy, is quantized.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The efficiency of a quantum well laser is greater than that of a bulk laser because the density of states function of electrons in the quantum well system has an abrupt edge that concentrates electrons in energy states that contribute to laser action.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Lasers containing more than one quantum well layer are known as *multiple quantum well* lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Multiple quantum wells improve the overlap of the gain region with the optical waveguide mode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Further improvements in laser efficiency have also been demonstrated by reducing the quantum well layer(s) to a layer(s) with quantum wires and especially quantum dots.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In a quantum cascade laser, the difference between quantum well energy levels is used for the laser transition instead of the bandgap.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This enables laser action at relatively long wavelengths, which can be tuned simply by altering the thickness of the layer.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] An interband cascade laser (ICL) is a type of laser diode that can produce coherent radiation over a large part of the mid-infrared region of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The problem with the simple quantum well diode described above is that the thin layer is simply too small to effectively confine the light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] To compensate, another two layers are added on, outside the first three.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] These layers have a lower refractive index than the center layers, and hence confine the light effectively.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Such a design is called a separate confinement heterostructure (SCH) laser diode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Almost all commercial laser diodes since the 1990s have been SCH quantum well diodes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] A distributed Bragg reflector laser (DBR) is a type of single-frequency laser diode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] It is characterized by an optical cavity consisting of an electrically or optically pumped gain region between two mirrors to provide feedback.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] One of the mirrors is a broadband reflector and the other mirror is wavelength selective so that gain is favored on a single longitudinal mode, resulting in lasing at a single resonant frequency.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The broadband mirror is usually coated with a low-reflectivity coating to allow emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The wavelength-selective mirror is a periodically structured diffraction grating with high reflectivity.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The diffraction grating is within a non-pumped, or passive, region of the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] A DBR laser is a monolithic single-chip device with the grating etched into the semiconductor.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] DBR lasers can be edge-emitting lasers or VCSELs.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Alternative hybrid architectures that share the same topology include extended-cavity diode lasers and volume Bragg grating lasers, but these are not properly called DBR lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] A distributed-feedback laser (DFB) is a type of single-frequency laser diode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] DFBs are the most common transmitter type in DWDM systems.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] To stabilize the lasing wavelength, a diffraction grating is etched close to the *p*–*n* junction of the diode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This grating acts like an optical filter, causing a single wavelength to be fed back to the gain region and lase.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Since the grating provides the feedback that is required for lasing, reflection from the facets is not required.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Thus, at least one facet of a DFB is anti-reflection coated.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The DFB laser has a stable wavelength that is set during manufacturing by the pitch of the grating, and can only be tuned slightly with temperature.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] DFB lasers are widely used in optical communication applications where a precise and stable wavelength is critical.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The threshold current of this DFB laser, based on its static characteristic, is around 11 mA.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The appropriate bias current in a linear regime could be taken in the middle of the static characteristic (50 mA).
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Several techniques have been proposed in order to enhance the single-mode operation in these kinds of lasers by inserting a one-phase-shift (1PS) or multiple-phase-shift (MPS) in the uniform Bragg grating.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] However, multiple-phase-shift DFB lasers represent the optimal solution because they have the combination of higher side-mode suppression ratio and reduced spatial hole-burning.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Vertical-cavity surface-emitting lasers (VCSELs) have the optical cavity axis along the direction of current flow rather than perpendicular to the current flow as in conventional laser diodes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The active region length is very short compared with the lateral dimensions so that the radiation emerges from the surface of the cavity rather than from its edge as shown in the figure.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The reflectors at the ends of the cavity are dielectric mirrors made from alternating high- and low-refractive-index quarter-wave-thick multilayer.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] But there is a disadvantage: because of the high mirror reflectivities, VCSELs have lower output powers when compared to edge-emitting lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] There are several advantages to producing VCSELs when compared with the production process of edge-emitting lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Edge-emitters cannot be tested until the end of the production process.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] If the edge-emitter does not work, whether due to bad contacts or poor material growth quality, then the production time and the processing materials have been wasted.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Additionally, because VCSELs emit the beam perpendicular to the active region of the laser as opposed to parallel as with an edge emitter, tens of thousands of VCSELs can be processed simultaneously on a three-inch gallium arsenide wafer.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Furthermore, even though the VCSEL production process is more labor- and material-intensive, the yield can be controlled to a more predictable outcome.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] However, they normally show a lower power output level.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Vertical-external-cavity surface-emitting lasers, or VECSELs, are similar to VCSELs.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In VCSELs, the mirrors are typically grown epitaxially as part of the diode structure, or grown separately and bonded directly to the semiconductor containing the active region.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] VECSELs are distinguished by a construction in which one of the two mirrors is external to the diode structure.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] As a result, the cavity includes a free-space region.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] A typical distance from the diode to the external mirror would be 1 cm.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] One of the most interesting features of any VECSEL is the small thickness of the semiconductor gain region in the direction of propagation, less than 100 nm.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In contrast, a conventional in-plane semiconductor laser entails light propagation over distances of from 250 μm upward to 2 mm or longer.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The significance of the short propagation distance is that it causes the effect of *antiguiding* nonlinearities in the diode laser gain region to be minimized.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The result is a large-cross-section single-mode optical beam that is not attainable from in-plane ("edge-emitting") diode lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Several workers demonstrated optically pumped VECSELs, and they continue to be developed for many applications, including high-power sources for use in industrial machining (cutting, punching, etc.) because of their unusually high power and efficiency when pumped by multi-mode diode laser bars.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] However, because of their lack of *p*–*n* junctions, optically pumped VECSELs are not considered *diode lasers*, and are classified as semiconductor lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Electrically pumped VECSELs have also been demonstrated.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Applications for electrically pumped VECSELs include projection displays, served by frequency doubling of near-IR VECSEL emitters to produce blue and green light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] External-cavity diode lasers (ECDLs) are tunable lasers which utilize a resonant optical cavity to feed light back to the laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The first external-cavity diode lasers used intracavity etalons and simple tuning Littrow gratings.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Other designs include gratings in grazing-incidence configuration, multiple-prism grating configurations, and piezo-transduced diode laser configuration.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Laser diodes have the same reliability and failure issues as light-emitting diodes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In addition, they are subject to *catastrophic optical damage* COD, when operated at higher power.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Many of the advances in reliability of diode lasers in the last 20 years remain proprietary to their developers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] *Reverse engineering* is not always able to reveal the differences between more-reliable and less-reliable diode laser products.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Semiconductor lasers can be surface-emitting lasers such as VCSELs, or in-plane edge-emitting lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] For edge-emitting lasers, the edge facet mirror is often formed by cleaving the semiconductor wafer to form a specularly reflecting plane.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This approach is facilitated by the weakness of the [110] crystallographic plane in III-V semiconductor crystals, such as GaAs, InP, GaSb, etc. compared to the other planes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The atomic states at the cleavage plane are altered compared to their bulk properties within the crystal by the termination of the perfectly periodic lattice at that plane.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Surface states at the cleaved plane have energy levels within the otherwise forbidden bandgap of the semiconductor.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Thus, when light propagates through the cleavage plane and transits to free space from within the semiconductor crystal a fraction of the light energy is absorbed by the surface states, where it is converted to the heat by phonon-electron interactions.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In addition, the mirror may heat simply because the edge of the diode laser—which is electrically pumped—is in less-than-perfect contact with the mount that provides a path for heat removal.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The heating of the mirror causes the bandgap of the semiconductor to shrink in the warmer areas.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The bandgap shrinkage brings more electronic band-to-band transitions into alignment with the photon energy, causing yet more absorption.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This is thermal runaway, a form of the positive feedback, and the result can be melting of the facet, known as *catastrophic optical damage* - COD.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In the 1970s, this problem, which is particularly nettlesome for GaAs-based lasers emitting between 0.630 μm and 1 μm (less so for InP-based lasers used for long-haul telecommunications, which emit between 1.3 μm and 2 μm), was identified.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Michael Ettenberg, a researcher and later Vice President at RCA Laboratories' David Sarnoff Research Center in Princeton, New Jersey devised a solution.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] A thin layer of aluminum oxide was deposited on the facet.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] If the aluminum oxide thickness is chosen correctly, it functions as an anti-reflective coating, reducing reflection at the surface.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This alleviated the heating and COD at the facet.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Since then, various other refinements have been employed.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] One approach is to create a so-called non-absorbing mirror (NAM) such that the final 10 μm or so before the light emits from the cleaved facet are rendered non-absorbing at the wavelength of the interest.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In the very early 1990s, SDL Inc. began supplying high-power diode lasers with good reliability characteristics.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] CEO Donald Scifres and CTO David Welch presented new reliability performance data at, e.g., SPIE Photonics West conferences of the era.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The methods used by SDL to defeat COD were considered to be highly proprietary and were still undisclosed publicly as June of 2006.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] In the mid-1990s, IBM Research - Ruschlikon, Switzerland announced that it had devised its so-called *E2 process*, which conferred extraordinary resistance to the COD in GaAs-based lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] This process also was undisclosed as of June 2006.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Reliability of high-power diode laser pump bars (used to pump solid-state lasers) remains difficult problem in the variety of applications, in spite of these proprietary advances.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Indeed, the physics of diode laser failure is still being worked out, and research on this subject remains active, if proprietary.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Extension of the lifetime of laser diodes is critical to their continued adaptation to a wide variety of applications.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Laser diodes are numerically the most common laser type, with 2004 sales of approximately 733 million units, as compared to 131,000 of other types of lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Laser diodes are widely used in telecommunications as easily modulated and easily coupled light sources for fiber-optic communication.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] They are used in various measuring instruments, such as rangefinders.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Another common use is in barcode readers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Visible lasers, typically red but later also green, are common as laser pointers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Both low- and high-power diodes are used extensively in the printing industry, both as light sources for scanning (input) of images and for very-high-speed and high-resolution printing plate (output) manufacturing.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Infrared and red laser diodes are common in CD players, CD-ROMs, and DVD technology.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Violet lasers are used in HD DVD and Blu-ray technology.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Diode lasers have also found many applications in laser absorption spectrometry (LAS) for high-speed, low-cost assessment or monitoring of the concentration of various species in gas phase.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] High-power laser diodes are used in industrial applications such as heat treating, cladding, seam welding, and for pumping other lasers, such as diode-pumped solid-state lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Uses of laser diodes can be categorized in various ways.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Most applications could be served by larger solid-state lasers or optical parametric oscillators, but the low cost of mass-produced diode lasers makes them essential for mass-market applications.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Diode lasers can be used in a great many fields; since light has many different properties (power, wavelength, spectral and beam quality, polarization, etc.), it is useful to classify applications by these basic properties.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Many applications of diode lasers primarily make use of the *directed energy* property of the optical beam.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Some of the above applications are well-established, while others are emerging.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Laser medicine: medicine and especially dentistry have found many new uses for diode lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The shrinking size and cost of the units and their increasing user-friendliness makes them very attractive to clinicians for minor soft-tissue procedures.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Diode wavelengths range from 810 to 1,100 nm, are poorly absorbed by soft tissue, and are not used for cutting or ablation.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Soft tissue is not cut by the laser's beam, but is instead cut by contact with a hot charred glass tip.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] The laser's irradiation is highly absorbed at the distal end of the tip and heats it up to 500–900°C.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Because the tip is so hot, it can be used to cut soft tissue and can cause hemostasis through cauterization and carbonization.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Diode lasers when used on soft tissue can cause extensive collateral thermal damage to surrounding tissue.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] As laser beam light is inherently coherent, certain applications use the coherence of laser diodes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] These include interferometric distance measurement, holography, coherent communications, and coherent control of chemical reactions.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Laser diodes are used for their ability to generate ultra-short pulses of light by the technique known as *mode-locking*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-diode] Laser diodes are used as a light source for maskless photolithography.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A **laser** is a device that emits light through a process of optical amplification based on the stimulated emission of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The word *laser* originated as an acronym for **light amplification by stimulated emission of radiation**.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The first laser was built in 1960 by Theodore Maiman at Hughes Research Laboratories, based on theoretical work by Charles H.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Townes and Arthur Leonard Schawlow and the optical amplifier patented by Gordon Gould.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A laser differs from other sources of light in that it emits light that is *coherent*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Spatial coherence allows a laser to be focused to a tight spot, enabling uses such as optical communication, laser cutting, and lithography.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] It also allows a laser beam to stay narrow over great distances (collimation), used in laser pointers, lidar, and free-space optical communication.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Lasers can also have high temporal coherence, which permits them to emit light with a very narrow frequency spectrum.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Temporal coherence can also be used to produce ultrashort pulses of light with a broad spectrum but durations measured in attoseconds.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The laser is regarded as one of the greatest inventions of the 20th century.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The first device using amplification by stimulated emission operated at microwave frequencies, and was called a *maser*, for "microwave amplification by stimulated emission of radiation".
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] When similar optical devices were developed they were first called *optical masers*, until "microwave" was replaced by "light" in the acronym, to become *laser*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Today, all such devices operating at frequencies higher than microwaves (approximately above 300 GHz) are called lasers (e.g.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] *infrared lasers*, *ultraviolet lasers*, *X-ray lasers*, *gamma-ray lasers*), whereas devices operating at microwave or lower radio frequencies are called masers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The back-formed verb "to lase" is frequently used in the field, meaning "to give off coherent light," especially about the gain medium of a laser; when a laser is operating, it is said to be "lasing".
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The terms *laser* and *maser* are also used for naturally occurring coherent emissions, as in *astrophysical maser* and *atom laser*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A laser that produces light by itself is technically an optical oscillator rather than an optical amplifier as suggested by the acronym.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] It has been humorously noted that the acronym LOSER, for "light oscillation by stimulated emission of radiation", would have been more correct.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Some sources refer to the word laser as an anacronym, meaning an acronym so widely used as a noun that it is no longer considered an abbreviation.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Photons, the quanta of electromagnetic radiation, are released and absorbed from energy levels in atoms and molecules.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In a lightbulb or a star, the energy is emitted from many different levels giving photons with a broad range of energies.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This process is called thermal radiation.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The underlying physical process creating photons in a laser is the same as in thermal radiation, but the actual emission is not the result of random thermal processes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Instead, the release of a photon is triggered by the nearby passage of another photon.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] For this process to work, the passing photon must be similar in energy, and thus wavelength, to the one that could be released by the atom or molecule, and the atom or molecule must be in the suitable excited state.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The photon that is emitted by stimulated emission is identical to the photon that triggered its emission, and both photons can go on to trigger stimulated emission in other atoms, creating the possibility of a chain reaction.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] For this to happen, many of the atoms or molecules must be in the proper excited state so that the photons can trigger them.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In most materials, atoms or molecules drop out of excited states fairly rapidly, making it difficult or impossible to produce a chain reaction.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The materials chosen for lasers are the ones that have metastable states, which stay excited for a relatively long time.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In laser physics, such a material is called an active laser medium.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Combined with an energy source that continues to "pump" energy into the material, it is possible to have enough atoms or molecules in an excited state for a chain reaction to develop.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Lasers are distinguished from other light sources by their coherence.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Spatial (or transverse) coherence is typically expressed through the output being a narrow beam, which is diffraction-limited.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Laser beams can be focused to very tiny spots, achieving a very high irradiance, or they can have a very low divergence to concentrate their power at a great distance.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Temporal (or longitudinal) coherence implies a polarized wave at a single frequency, whose phase is correlated over a relatively great distance (the coherence length) along the beam.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A beam produced by a thermal or other incoherent light source has an instantaneous amplitude and phase that vary randomly with respect to time and position, thus having a short coherence length.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Lasers are characterized according to their wavelength in a vacuum.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Most "single wavelength" lasers produce radiation in several *modes* with slightly different wavelengths.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Although temporal coherence implies some degree of monochromaticity, some lasers emit a broad spectrum of light or emit different wavelengths of light simultaneously.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Certain lasers are not single spatial mode and have light beams that diverge more than is required by the diffraction limit.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] All such devices are classified as "lasers" based on the method of producing light by stimulated emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Lasers are employed where light of the required spatial or temporal coherence can not be produced using simpler technologies.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A laser consists of a gain medium, a mechanism to energize the gain medium, and something to provide optical feedback.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The gain medium is a material with properties that allow it to amplify light by way of stimulated emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Light of a specific wavelength that passes through the gain medium is amplified (i.e., its power increases).
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Feedback enables stimulated emission to amplify predominantly the optical frequency at the peak of the gain-frequency curve.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] As stimulated emission grows, eventually one frequency dominates over all others, meaning that a coherent beam has been formed.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The process of stimulated emission is analogous to that of an audio oscillator with positive feedback which can occur, for example, when the speaker in a public-address system is placed in proximity to the microphone.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The screech one hears is audio oscillation at the peak of the gain-frequency curve for the amplifier.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] For the gain medium to amplify light, it needs to be supplied with energy in a process called pumping.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The energy is typically supplied as an electric current or as light at a different wavelength.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Pump light may be provided by a flash lamp or by another laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The most common type of laser uses feedback from an optical cavity—a pair of mirrors on either end of the gain medium.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Light bounces back and forth between the mirrors, passing through the gain medium and being amplified each time.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Typically one of the two mirrors, the output coupler, is partially transparent.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Some of the light escapes through this mirror.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Depending on the design of the cavity (whether the mirrors are flat or curved), the light coming out of the laser may spread out or form a narrow beam.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In analogy to electronic oscillators, this device is sometimes called a *laser oscillator*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Most practical lasers contain additional elements that affect the properties of the emitted light, such as the polarization, wavelength, and shape of the beam.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] An atom has discrete or quantum energy levels.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] An atom can absorb energy from light (photons) or heat (phonons) only if there is a transition between energy levels that match the energy carried by the photon or phonon.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] For light, this means that any given transition will only absorb one particular wavelength of light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Photons with the correct wavelength can cause a jump from the lower to the higher energy level.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In a system in thermodynamic equilibrium, absorption events are balanced by spontaneous emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A third process also operates: photon with the correct wavelength to be absorbed by a transition can trigger stimulated emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The energy level of the atom drops from the higher to the lower level, emitting a photon that matches the original photon in wavelength, phase, and polarization direction.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A laser uses an energy source to excite many atoms to the higher energy state so that spontaneous emission from one atom can trigger a cascade of multiple stimulated emission events, generating a large number of photons at the same wavelength, phase and polarization.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A simple physical model for a laser begins with Albert Einstein's 1917 quantum theory of radiation.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Einstein adopted only one quantum assumption from Bohr's model of the atoms, that they exist in stationary states.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Einstein treats the interaction between these atoms and a radiation field using Max Planck's classical oscillator, in effect replacing the non-specific oscillators of Planck's law with Bohr atoms.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The relative phase of an oscillator and electromagnetic field determines the direction energy flows during the interaction.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Einstein adds a third constant, $A_{ba}$ , independent of the flux density, corresponding to emission in the absence of the field.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Some of the $N_{b}$ atoms will spontaneously emit light and others will respond with stimulated emission creating an avalanche of photons in phase.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The gain medium is put into an excited state by an external source of energy.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In most lasers, this medium consists of a population of atoms that have been excited into such a state using an outside light source, or an electrical field that supplies energy for atoms to absorb and be transformed into their excited states.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The gain medium of a laser is normally a material of controlled purity, size, concentration, and shape, which amplifies the beam by the process of stimulated emission described above.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This material can be of any state: gas, liquid, solid, or plasma.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The gain medium absorbs pump energy, which raises some electrons into higher energy ("excited") quantum states.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Particles can interact with light by either absorbing or emitting photons.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Emission can be spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In the latter case, the photon is emitted in the same direction as the light that is passing by.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] When the number of particles in one excited state exceeds the number of particles in some lower-energy state, population inversion is achieved.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This situation results in light amplification from the atoms in excited states because there are more stimulated emissions than absorptions.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Population inversion cannot occur in a two-level energy system: as the upper level is populated, the probability of stimulated emission increases.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This prevents population inversion as the number of atoms transitioning from excited to relaxed states would be the same, deeming the process inefficient.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Lasers instead use three-level or higher systems, where the additional energy level allows electrons to relax quickly and produce a consistent population inversion.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A system with this property is called an optical amplifier.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] When an optical amplifier is placed inside a resonant optical cavity, one obtains a laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] For lasing media with extremely high gain, so-called superluminescence, light can be sufficiently amplified in a single pass through the gain medium without requiring a resonator.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Although often referred to as a laser (see, for example, nitrogen laser), the light output from such a device lacks the spatial and temporal coherence achievable with lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Such a device cannot be described as an oscillator but rather as a high-gain optical amplifier that amplifies its spontaneous emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The same mechanism describes so-called astrophysical masers/lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The optical resonator is sometimes referred to as an "optical cavity", but this is a misnomer: lasers use open resonators as opposed to the literal cavity that would be employed at microwave frequencies in a maser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The resonator typically consists of two mirrors between which a coherent beam of light travels in both directions, reflecting on itself so that an average photon will pass through the gain medium repeatedly before it is emitted from the output aperture or lost to diffraction or absorption.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] If the gain (amplification) in the medium is larger than the resonator losses, then the power of the recirculating light can rise exponentially.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] But each stimulated emission event returns an atom from its excited state to the ground state, reducing the gain of the medium.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] With increasing beam power, the net gain (gain minus loss) reduces to unity and the gain medium is said to be saturated.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In a continuous wave (CW) laser, the balance of pump power against gain saturation and cavity losses produces an equilibrium value of the laser power inside the cavity; this equilibrium determines the operating point of the laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] If the applied pump power is too small, the gain will never be sufficient to overcome the cavity losses, and laser light will not be produced.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The minimum pump power needed to begin laser action is called the *lasing threshold*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The gain medium will amplify any photons passing through it, regardless of direction; but only the photons in a spatial mode supported by the resonator will pass more than once through the medium and receive substantial amplification.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In most lasers, lasing begins with spontaneous emission into the lasing mode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This initial light is then amplified by stimulated emission in the gain medium.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Stimulated emission produces light that matches the input signal in direction, wavelength, and polarization, whereas the phase of the emitted light is 90 degrees in lead of the stimulating light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This, combined with the filtering effect of the optical resonator gives laser light its characteristic coherence, and may give it uniform polarization and monochromaticity, depending on the resonator's design.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The fundamental laser linewidth of light emitted from the lasing resonator can be orders of magnitude narrower than the linewidth of light emitted from the passive resonator.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Some lasers use a separate injection seeder to start the process off with a beam that is already highly coherent.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This can produce beams with a narrower spectrum than would otherwise be possible.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Glauber showed that coherent states are formed from combinations of photon number states, for which he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A coherent beam of light is formed by single-frequency quantum photon states distributed according to a Poisson distribution.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] As a result, the arrival rate of photons in a laser beam is described by Poisson statistics.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Many lasers produce a beam that can be approximated as a Gaussian beam; such beams have the minimum divergence possible for a given beam diameter.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Some lasers, particularly high-power ones, produce multimode beams, with the transverse modes often approximated using Hermite–Gaussian or Laguerre-Gaussian functions.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Some high-power lasers use a flat-topped profile known as a "tophat beam".
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Unstable laser resonators (not used in most lasers) produce fractal-shaped beams.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Specialized optical systems can produce more complex beam geometries, such as Bessel beams and optical vortexes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Near the "waist" (or focal region) of a laser beam, it is highly *collimated*: the wavefronts are planar, normal to the direction of propagation, with no beam divergence at that point.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] However, due to diffraction, that can only remain true well within the Rayleigh range.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The beam of a single transverse mode (gaussian beam) laser eventually diverges at an angle that varies inversely with the beam diameter, as required by diffraction theory.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Thus, the "pencil beam" directly generated by a common helium–neon laser would spread out to a size of perhaps 500 kilometers when shone on the Moon (from the distance of the Earth).
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] On the other hand, the light from a semiconductor laser typically exits the tiny crystal with a large divergence: up to 50°.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] However even such a divergent beam can be transformed into a similarly collimated beam employing a lens system, as is always included, for instance, in a laser pointer whose light originates from a laser diode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] That is possible due to the light being of a single spatial mode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This unique property of laser light, spatial coherence, cannot be replicated using standard light sources (except by discarding most of the light) as can be appreciated by comparing the beam from a flashlight (torch) or spotlight to that of almost any laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A laser beam profiler is used to measure the intensity profile, width, and divergence of laser beams.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Diffuse reflection of a laser beam from a matte surface produces a speckle pattern with interesting properties.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The mechanism of producing radiation in a laser relies on stimulated emission, where energy is extracted from a transition in an atom or molecule.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Stimulated emission is a quantum phenomenon that was predicted by Albert Einstein, who derived the relationship between the *A* coefficient, describing spontaneous emission, and the *B* coefficient which applies to absorption and stimulated emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In the absence of an electric field, the spontaneous emission coefficient, A21, is the probability per unit time of emission due to a transition from an excited state (level 2) to the ground state (level 1).
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In an electric field both emission and absorption is possible.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] B21 is the probability of the emission; B12 is the probability of the absorption.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A laser can be classified as operating in either continuous or pulsed mode, depending on whether the power output is essentially continuous over time or whether its output takes the form of pulses of light on one or another time scale.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Of course, even a laser whose output is normally continuous can be intentionally turned on and off at some rate to create pulses of light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] When the modulation rate is on time scales much slower than the cavity lifetime and the period over which energy can be stored in the lasing medium or pumping mechanism, then it is still classified as a "modulated" or "pulsed" continuous wave laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Most laser diodes used in communication systems fall into that category.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Some applications of lasers depend on a beam whose output power is constant over time.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Such a laser is known as a *continuous-wave* (*CW*) laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Many types of lasers can be made to operate in continuous-wave mode to satisfy such an application.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In most cases, these lasers are still termed "continuous-wave" as their output power is steady when averaged over longer periods, with the very high-frequency power variations having little or no impact on the intended application.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] For continuous-wave operation, the population inversion of the gain medium needs to be continually replenished by a steady pump source.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In some lasing media, this is impossible.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In some other lasers, it would require pumping the laser at a very high continuous power level, which would be impractical, or destroying the laser by producing excessive heat.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The pulsed operation of lasers refers to any laser not classified as a continuous wave so that the optical power appears in pulses of some duration at some repetition rate.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This encompasses a wide range of technologies addressing many different motivations.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Some lasers are pulsed simply because they cannot be run in continuous mode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In other cases, the application requires the production of pulses having as large an energy as possible.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Since the pulse energy is equal to the average power divided by the repetition rate, this goal can sometimes be satisfied by lowering the rate of pulses so that more energy can be built up between pulses.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Other applications rely on the peak pulse power (rather than the energy in the pulse), especially to obtain nonlinear optical effects.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] For a given pulse energy, this requires creating pulses of the shortest possible duration utilizing techniques such as Q-switching.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The optical bandwidth of a pulse cannot be narrower than the reciprocal of the pulse width.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In the case of extremely short pulses, that implies lasing over a considerable bandwidth, quite contrary to the very narrow bandwidths typical of CW lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The lasing medium in some *dye lasers* and *vibronic solid-state lasers* produces optical gain over a wide bandwidth, making a laser possible that can thus generate pulses of light as short as a few femtoseconds (10−15 s).
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In a Q-switched laser, the population inversion is allowed to build up by introducing loss inside the resonator which exceeds the gain of the medium; this can also be described as a reduction of the quality factor or 'Q' of the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This results in a short pulse incorporating that energy, and thus a high peak power.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] A mode-locked laser is capable of emitting extremely short pulses on the order of tens of picoseconds down to less than 10 femtoseconds.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] These pulses repeat at the round-trip time, that is, the time that it takes light to complete one round trip between the mirrors comprising the resonator.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Due to the Fourier limit (also known as energy–time uncertainty), a pulse of such short temporal length has a spectrum spread over a considerable bandwidth.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Thus such a gain medium must have a gain bandwidth sufficiently broad to amplify those frequencies.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] An example of a suitable material is titanium-doped, artificially grown sapphire (Ti:sapphire), which has a very wide gain bandwidth and can thus produce pulses of only a few femtoseconds duration.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Unlike the giant pulse of a Q-switched laser, consecutive pulses from a mode-locked laser are phase-coherent; that is, the pulses (and not just their envelopes) are identical and perfectly periodic.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] For this reason, and the extremely large peak powers attained by such short pulses, such lasers are invaluable in certain areas of research.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Another method of achieving pulsed laser operation is to pump the laser material with a source that is itself pulsed, either through electronic charging in the case of flash lamps, or another laser that is already pulsed.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Pulsed pumping was historically used with dye lasers where the inverted population lifetime of a dye molecule was so short that a high-energy, fast pump was needed.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The way to overcome this problem was to charge up large capacitors which are then switched to discharge through flashlamps, producing an intense flash.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Pulsed pumping is also required for three-level lasers in which the lower energy level rapidly becomes highly populated, preventing further lasing until those atoms relax to the ground state.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] These lasers, such as the excimer laser and the copper vapor laser, can never be operated in CW mode.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Ladenburg confirmed the existence of the phenomena of stimulated emission and negative absorption.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Fabrikant predicted using stimulated emission to amplify "short" waves.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Retherford found apparent stimulated emission in hydrogen spectra and effected the first demonstration of stimulated emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In 1950, Alfred Kastler (Nobel Prize for Physics 1966) proposed the method of optical pumping, which was experimentally demonstrated two years later by Brossel, Kastler, and Winter.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In 1951, Joseph Weber submitted a paper on using stimulated emissions to make a microwave amplifier to the June 1952 Institute of Radio Engineers Vacuum Tube Research Conference in Ottawa, Ontario, Canada.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] After this presentation, RCA asked Weber to give a seminar on this idea, and Charles H.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Townes asked him for a copy of the paper.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Zeiger produced the first microwave amplifier, a device operating on similar principles to the laser, but amplifying microwave radiation rather than infrared or visible radiation.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Townes's maser was incapable of continuous output.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Meanwhile, in the Soviet Union, Nikolay Basov and Aleksandr Prokhorov were independently working on the quantum oscillator and solved the problem of continuous-output systems by using more than two energy levels.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] These gain media could release stimulated emissions between an excited state and a lower excited state, not the ground state, facilitating the maintenance of a population inversion.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In 1955, Prokhorov and Basov suggested optical pumping of a multi-level system as a method for obtaining the population inversion, later a main method of laser pumping.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Townes reports that several eminent physicists—among them Niels Bohr, John von Neumann, and Llewellyn Thomas—argued the maser violated Heisenberg's uncertainty principle and hence could not work.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Others such as Isidor Rabi and Polykarp Kusch expected that it would be impractical and not worth the effort.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Townes, Nikolay Basov, and Aleksandr Prokhorov shared the Nobel Prize in Physics, "for fundamental work in the field of quantum electronics, which has led to the construction of oscillators and amplifiers based on the maser–laser principle".
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In April 1957, Japanese engineer Jun-ichi Nishizawa proposed the concept of a "semiconductor optical maser" in a patent application.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Townes and Arthur Leonard Schawlow, then at Bell Labs, began a serious study of infrared "optical masers".
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] As ideas developed, they abandoned infrared radiation to instead concentrate on visible light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Simultaneously, Columbia University graduate student Gordon Gould was working on a doctoral thesis about the energy levels of excited thallium.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Gould and Townes met and talked about radiation emission as a general subject, but not the specific work they were pursuing.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Later, in November 1957, Gould noted his ideas for how a "laser" could be made, including using an open resonator (an essential laser-device component).
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] His notebook included a diagram of an optically pumped laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] It also contained the first recorded use of the term "laser," an acronym for "light amplification by stimulated emission of radiation," along with suggestions for potential applications of the coherent light beams described.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In 1958, Bell Labs filed a patent application for Schawlow and Townes's proposed optical maser; and Schawlow and Townes published a paper with their theoretical calculations in the *Physical Review*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] That same year, Prokhorov independently proposed using an open resonator, the first published appearance of this idea.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] At a conference in 1959, Gordon Gould first published the acronym "LASER" in the paper *The LASER, Light Amplification by Stimulated Emission of Radiation*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Gould's intention was that different "-ASER" acronyms should be used for different parts of the spectrum: "XASER" for x-rays, "UVASER" for ultraviolet, "RASER" for radio-wave, etc.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Instead, the term "LASER" ended up being used for all devices operating at wavelengths shorter than microwaves.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Gould's notes included possible applications for a laser, such as optical telecommunications, spectrometry, interferometry, radar, and nuclear fusion.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] He continued developing the idea and filed a patent application in April 1959.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) denied his application, and awarded a patent to Bell Labs, in 1960.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] That provoked a twenty-eight-year legal fight over the rights to various laser technologies and applications.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Gould won his first patent in 1977 for optically pumped laser amplifiers, yet it was not until 1987 that he won his first significant patent infringement claim.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Many aspects of a working laser were patented by different people: the question of just how to assign credit for inventing the laser remains unresolved by historians.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Maiman operated the first functioning laser at Hughes Research Laboratories, Malibu, California, ahead of several research teams, including those of Townes, at Columbia University, Arthur L.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Schawlow, at Bell Labs, and Gould, at the TRG (Technical Research Group) company.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Maiman's functional laser used a flashlamp-pumped synthetic ruby crystal to produce red laser light at 694 nanometers wavelength.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The device was only capable of pulsed operation, due to its three-level pumping design scheme.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Later that year, the Iranian physicist Ali Javan, and William R.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Herriott, constructed the first gas laser, using helium and neon that was capable of continuous operation in the infrared (U.S.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Patent 3,149,290); later, Javan received the Albert Einstein World Award of Science in 1993.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Hall demonstrated the first semiconductor laser, which was made of gallium arsenide and emitted in the near-infrared band of the spectrum at 850 nm.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Later that year, Nick Holonyak Jr. demonstrated the first semiconductor laser with a visible emission.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] This first semiconductor laser could only be used in pulsed-beam operation, and when cooled to liquid nitrogen temperatures (77 K).
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Patel at Bell Telephone Laboratories invented the carbon-dioxide (CO2) laser, the first high-power continuous-wave gas laser, which went on to become one of the most widely used industrial and medical lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In 1970, Zhores Alferov, in the USSR, and Izuo Hayashi and Morton Panish of Bell Labs also independently developed room-temperature, continual-operation diode lasers, using the heterojunction structure.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Research on improving these aspects of lasers continues to this day.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In 2015, researchers made a white laser, whose light is modulated by a synthetic nanosheet made out of zinc, cadmium, sulfur, and selenium that can emit red, green, and blue light in varying proportions, with each wavelength spanning 191 nm.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In 2017, researchers at the Delft University of Technology demonstrated an AC Josephson junction microwave laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] Since the laser operates in the superconducting regime, it is more stable than other semiconductor-based lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] The device has the potential for applications in quantum computing.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p01] In 2017, researchers at the Technical University of Munich demonstrated the smallest mode locking laser capable of emitting pairs of phase-locked picosecond laser pulses with a repetition frequency up to 200 GHz.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Following the invention of the HeNe gas laser, many other gas discharges have been found to amplify light coherently.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Gas lasers using many different gases have been built and used for many purposes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The helium–neon laser (HeNe) can operate at many different wavelengths, however, the vast majority are engineered to lase at 633 nm; these relatively low-cost but highly coherent lasers are extremely common in optical research and educational laboratories.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Commercial carbon dioxide (CO2) lasers can emit many hundreds of watts in a single spatial mode which can be concentrated into a tiny spot.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This emission is in the thermal infrared at 10.6 μm; such lasers are regularly used in industry for cutting, welding, and medical applications.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The efficiency of a CO2 laser is unusually high: over 30%.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Argon-ion lasers can operate at several lasing transitions between 351 and 528.7 nm.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Depending on the optical design one or more of these transitions can be lasing simultaneously; the most commonly used lines are 458 nm, 488 nm and 514.5 nm.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] A nitrogen transverse electrical discharge in gas at atmospheric pressure (TEA) laser is an inexpensive gas laser, often home-built by hobbyists, which produces rather incoherent UV light at 337.1 nm.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Metal ion lasers are gas lasers that generate deep ultraviolet wavelengths.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Helium-silver (HeAg) 224 nm and neon-copper (NeCu) 248 nm are two examples.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Like all low-pressure gas lasers, the gain media of these lasers have quite narrow oscillation linewidths, less than 3 GHz (0.5 picometers), making them candidates for use in fluorescence suppressed Raman spectroscopy.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Lasing without maintaining the medium excited into a population inversion was demonstrated in 1992 in sodium gas and again in 1995 in rubidium gas by various international teams.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This was accomplished by using an external maser to induce "optical transparency" in the medium by introducing and destructively interfering the ground electron transitions between two paths so that the likelihood for the ground electrons to absorb any energy has been canceled.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Chemical lasers are powered by a chemical reaction permitting a large amount of energy to be released quickly.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Such very high-power lasers are especially of interest to the military; however continuous wave chemical lasers at very high power levels, fed by streams of gasses, have been developed and have some industrial applications.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] As examples, in the hydrogen fluoride laser (2700–2900 nm) and the deuterium fluoride laser (3800 nm) the reaction is the combination of hydrogen or deuterium gas with combustion products of ethylene in nitrogen trifluoride.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The first chemical laser was demonstrated in 1965 by Jerome V.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Pimentel at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] It was a hydrogen chloride laser operating at 3.7 micrometers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Excimer lasers are a special sort of gas laser powered by an electric discharge in which the lasing medium is an excimer, or more precisely an exciplex in existing designs.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] These are molecules that can only exist with one atom in an excited electronic state.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Once the molecule transfers its excitation energy to a photon, its atoms are no longer bound to each other, and the molecule disintegrates.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This drastically reduces the population of the lower energy state thus greatly facilitating a population inversion.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Excimers currently used are all noble gas compounds; noble gasses are chemically inert and can only form compounds while in an excited state.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Excimer lasers typically operate at ultraviolet wavelengths, with major applications including semiconductor photolithography and LASIK eye surgery.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Commonly used excimer molecules include ArF (emission at 193 nm), KrCl (222 nm), KrF (248 nm), XeCl (308 nm), and XeF (351 nm).
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The molecular fluorine laser, emitting at 157 nm in the vacuum ultraviolet, is sometimes referred to as an excimer laser; however, this appears to be a misnomer since F2 is a stable compound.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Solid-state lasers use a crystalline or glass rod that is "doped" with ions that provide the required energy states.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] For example, the first working laser was a ruby laser, made from ruby (chromium-doped corundum).
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The population inversion is maintained in the dopant.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] These materials are pumped optically using a shorter wavelength than the lasing wavelength, often from a flash tube or another laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The usage of the term "solid-state" in laser physics is narrower than in typical use.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Semiconductor lasers (laser diodes) are typically *not* referred to as solid-state lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Neodymium is a common dopant in various solid-state laser crystals, including yttrium orthovanadate (Nd:YVO4), yttrium lithium fluoride (Nd:YLF) and yttrium aluminium garnet (Nd:YAG).
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] All these lasers can produce high powers in the infrared spectrum at 1064 nm.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] They are used for cutting, welding, and marking of metals and other materials, and also in spectroscopy and for pumping dye lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] These lasers are also commonly doubled, tripled or quadrupled in frequency to produce 532 nm (green, visible), 355 nm and 266 nm (UV) beams, respectively.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Frequency-doubled diode-pumped solid-state (DPSS) lasers are used to make low power (<10 mW) bright green laser pointers, and high power (>3W) medical lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Ytterbium, holmium, thulium, and erbium are other common "dopants" in solid-state lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Ytterbium is used in crystals such as Yb:YAG, Yb:KGW, Yb:KYW, Yb:SYS, Yb:BOYS, Yb:CaF2, typically operating around 1020–1050 nm.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] They are potentially very efficient and high-powered due to a small quantum defect.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Extremely high powers in ultrashort pulses can be achieved with Yb:YAG.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Holmium-doped YAG crystals emit at 2097 nm and form an efficient laser operating at infrared wavelengths strongly absorbed by water-bearing tissues.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The Ho-YAG is usually operated in a pulsed mode and passed through optical fiber surgical devices to resurface joints, remove rot from teeth, vaporize cancers, and pulverize kidney and gall stones.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Titanium-doped sapphire (Ti:sapphire) produces a highly tunable infrared laser, commonly used for spectroscopy.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] It is also notable for use as a mode-locked laser producing ultrashort pulses of extremely high peak power.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Optical parametric oscillators shift the wavelength of solid-state lasers across the spectrum from ultraviolet to infrared.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Non-critically phase-matched OPOs can convert laser wavelengths with up to 70% efficiency, creating highly efficient lasers at so-called "eyesafe" wavelengths that enabled lasers to be used safely in public without eye damage.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Thermal limitations in solid-state lasers arise from unconverted pump power that heats the medium.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This heat, when coupled with a high thermo-optic coefficient (d*n*/d*T*) can cause thermal lensing and reduce the quantum efficiency.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Diode-pumped thin disk lasers overcome these issues by having a gain medium that is much thinner than the diameter of the pump beam.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This allows for a more uniform temperature in the material.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Thin disk lasers have been shown to produce beams of up to one kilowatt.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Solid-state lasers or laser amplifiers where the light is guided due to the total internal reflection in a single mode optical fiber are instead called fiber lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Guiding of light allows extremely long gain regions, providing good cooling conditions; fibers have a high surface area to volume ratio which allows efficient cooling.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] In addition, the fiber's waveguiding properties tend to reduce thermal distortion of the beam.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Erbium and ytterbium ions are common active species in such lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Quite often, the fiber laser is designed as a double-clad fiber.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This type of fiber consists of a fiber core, an inner cladding, and an outer cladding.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The index of the three concentric layers is chosen so that the fiber core acts as a single-mode fiber for the laser emission while the outer cladding acts as a highly multimode core for the pump laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This lets the pump propagate a large amount of power into and through the active inner core region while still having a high numerical aperture (NA) to have easy launching conditions.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Pump light can be used more efficiently by creating a fiber disk laser, or a stack of such lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Fiber lasers, like other optical media, can suffer from the effects of photodarkening when they are exposed to radiation of certain wavelengths.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] In particular, this can lead to degradation of the material and loss in laser functionality over time.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The exact causes and effects of this phenomenon vary from material to material, although it often involves the formation of color centers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Photonic crystal lasers are lasers based on nano-structures that provide the mode confinement and the density of optical states (DOS) structure required for the feedback to take place.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] They are typical micrometer-sized and tunable on the bands of the photonic crystals.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Semiconductor lasers are diodes that are electrically pumped.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Recombination of electrons and holes created by the applied current introduces optical gain.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Reflection from the ends of the crystal forms an optical resonator, although the resonator can be external to the semiconductor in some designs.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Commercial laser diodes emit at wavelengths from 375 nm to 3500 nm.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Low to medium power laser diodes are used in laser pointers, laser printers and CD/DVD players.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Laser diodes are also frequently used to optically pump other lasers with high efficiency.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The highest-power industrial laser diodes, with power of up to 20 kW, are used in industry for cutting and welding.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] External-cavity semiconductor lasers have a semiconductor active medium in a larger cavity.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] These devices can generate high power outputs with good beam quality, wavelength-tunable narrow-linewidth radiation, or ultrashort laser pulses.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] In 2012, Nichia and OSRAM developed and manufactured commercial high-power green laser diodes (515/520 nm), which compete with traditional diode-pumped solid-state lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Vertical cavity surface-emitting lasers (VCSELs) are semiconductor lasers whose emission direction is perpendicular to the surface of the wafer.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] VCSEL devices typically have a more circular output beam than conventional laser diodes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] As of 2005, only 850 nm VCSELs are widely available, with 1300 nm VCSELs beginning to be commercialized and 1550 nm devices being an area of research.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Quantum cascade lasers are semiconductor lasers that have an active transition between energy *sub-bands* of an electron in a structure containing several quantum wells.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The development of a silicon laser is important in the field of optical computing.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Silicon is the material of choice for integrated circuits, and so electronic and silicon photonic components (such as optical interconnects) could be fabricated on the same chip.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Unfortunately, silicon is a difficult lasing material to deal with, since it has certain properties which block lasing.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] However, recently teams have produced silicon lasers through methods such as fabricating the lasing material from silicon and other semiconductor materials, such as indium(III) phosphide or gallium(III) arsenide, materials that allow coherent light to be produced from silicon.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Recent developments have also shown the use of monolithically integrated nanowire lasers directly on silicon for optical interconnects, paving the way for chip-level applications.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] These heterostructure nanowire lasers capable of optical interconnects in silicon are also capable of emitting pairs of phase-locked picosecond pulses with a repetition frequency up to 200 GHz, allowing for on-chip optical signal processing.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Another type is a Raman laser, which takes advantage of Raman scattering to produce a laser from materials such as silicon.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Semiconductor quantum dot lasers use quantum dots as the active laser medium.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] These lasers exhibit device performance that is closer to gas lasers and avoid some of the disadvantages of traditional semiconductor laser media.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Improvements in modulation bandwidth, lasing threshold, relative intensity noise, linewidth enhancement factor and temperature insensitivity have all been observed.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The quantum dot active region may also be engineered to operate at different wavelengths by varying dot size and composition.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This allows quantum dot lasers to be fabricated to operate at wavelengths previously not possible using semiconductor laser technology.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Dye lasers use an organic dye as the gain medium.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The wide gain spectrum of available dyes, or mixtures of dyes, allows these lasers to be highly tunable, or to produce very short-duration pulses (on the order of a few femtoseconds).
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Although these tunable lasers are mainly known in their liquid form, researchers have also demonstrated narrow-linewidth tunable emission in dispersive oscillator configurations incorporating solid-state dye gain media.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] In their most prevalent form, these solid-state dye lasers use dye-doped polymers as laser media.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Bubble lasers are dye lasers that use a bubble as the optical resonator.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Whispering gallery modes in the bubble produce an output spectrum composed of hundreds of evenly spaced peaks: a frequency comb.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The spacing of the whispering gallery modes is directly related to the bubble circumference, allowing bubble lasers to be used as highly sensitive pressure sensors.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Free-electron lasers (FEL) generate coherent, high-power radiation that is widely tunable, currently ranging in wavelength from microwaves through terahertz radiation and infrared to the visible spectrum, to soft X-rays.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] They have the widest frequency range of any laser type.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] While FEL beams share the same optical traits as other lasers, such as coherent radiation, FEL operation is quite different.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Unlike gas, liquid, or solid-state lasers, which rely on bound atomic or molecular states, FELs use a relativistic electron beam as the lasing medium, hence the term *free-electron*.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The pursuit of a high-quantum-energy laser using transitions between isomeric states of an atomic nucleus has been the subject of wide-ranging academic research since the early 1970s.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Much of this is summarized in three review articles.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This research has been international in scope but mainly based in the former Soviet Union and the United States.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] While many scientists remain optimistic that a breakthrough is near, an operational gamma-ray laser is yet to be realized.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Some of the early studies were directed toward short pulses of neutrons exciting the upper isomer state in a solid so the gamma-ray transition could benefit from the line-narrowing of Mössbauer effect.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] In conjunction, several advantages were expected from two-stage pumping of a three-level system.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] It was conjectured that the nucleus of an atom embedded in the near field of a laser-driven coherently-oscillating electron cloud would experience a larger dipole field than that of the driving laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Furthermore, the nonlinearity of the oscillating cloud would produce both spatial and temporal harmonics, so nuclear transitions of higher multipolarity could also be driven at multiples of the laser frequency.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] In September 2007, the BBC News reported that there was speculation about the possibility of using positronium annihilation to drive a very powerful gamma ray laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] David Cassidy of the University of California, Riverside proposed that a single such laser could be used to ignite a nuclear fusion reaction, replacing the banks of hundreds of lasers currently employed in inertial confinement fusion experiments.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Space-based X-ray lasers pumped by nuclear explosions have also been proposed as antimissile weapons.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Living cells have been used to produce laser light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The cells were genetically engineered to produce green fluorescent protein, which served as the laser's gain medium.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The cells were then placed between two 20-micrometer-wide mirrors, which acted as the laser cavity.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] When the cell was illuminated with blue light, it emitted intensely directed green laser light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Like astrophysical masers, irradiated planetary or stellar gases may amplify light producing a natural laser.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Mars, Venus, and MWC 349 exhibit this phenomenon.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] When the laser was first invented, it was called "a solution looking for a problem", although Gould noted numerous possible applications in his notebook and patent applications.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Since then, they have become ubiquitous, finding utility in thousands of highly varied applications in every section of modern society, including consumer electronics, information technology, science, medicine, industry, law enforcement, entertainment, and the military.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Fiber-optic communication relies on multiplexed lasers in dense wave-division multiplexing (WDM) systems to transmit large amounts of data over long distances.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The first widely noticeable use of lasers was the supermarket barcode scanner, introduced in 1974.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The laserdisc player, introduced in 1978, was the first successful consumer product to include a laser, but the compact disc player was the first laser-equipped device to become common, commercialized in 1982, followed shortly by laser printers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] In 2004, excluding diode lasers, approximately 131,000 lasers were sold, with a value of US$2.19 billion.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] In the same year, approximately 733 million diode lasers, valued at US$3.20 billion, were sold.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Global Industrial laser sales in 2023 reached $21.85 billion.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Lasers have many uses in medicine, including laser surgery (particularly eye surgery), curing blindness, laser healing (photobiomodulation therapy), kidney stone treatment, ophthalmoscopy, and cosmetic skin treatments such as acne treatment, cellulite and striae reduction, and hair removal.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Lasers are used to treat cancer by shrinking or destroying tumors or precancerous growths.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] They are most commonly used to treat superficial cancers that are on the surface of the body or the lining of internal organs.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] They are used to treat basal cell skin cancer and the very early stages of others like cervical, penile, vaginal, vulvar, and non-small cell lung cancer.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Laser therapy is often combined with other treatments, such as surgery, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Laser-induced interstitial thermotherapy (LITT), or interstitial laser photocoagulation, uses lasers to treat some cancers using hyperthermia, which uses heat to shrink tumors by damaging or killing cancer cells.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Lasers are more precise than traditional surgery methods and cause less damage, pain, bleeding, swelling, and scarring.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] A disadvantage is that surgeons must acquire specialized training, and thus it will likely be more expensive than other treatments.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Low-level laser therapy (LLLT) is a treatment in which low-power light from lasers or light-emitting diodes (LEDs) is applied to the surface of the body.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This is claimed to stimulate healing, relieve pain, and enhance cell function.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The effects appear to be limited to specific wavelengths of light.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The effectiveness of this form of treatment is still under investigation.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Repeated low-level red light therapy may be effective for controlling myopia in children.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Several such devices are cleared by the United States Food and Drug Administration (FDA), and low level red light therapy is being tested for treating a range of medical problems including rheumatoid arthritis and oral mucositis.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] A laser weapon is a type of directed-energy weapon that uses lasers to inflict damage.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Whether they will be deployed as practical, high-performance military weapons remains to be seen.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] One of the major issues with laser weapons is atmospheric thermal blooming, which is still largely unsolved.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] This issue is exacerbated when there is fog, smoke, dust, rain, snow, smog, foam, or purposely dispersed obscurant chemicals present.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The United States Navy has tested the very short range (1 mile), 30-kW Laser Weapon System or LaWS to be used against targets like small UAVs, rocket-propelled grenades, and visible motorboat or helicopter engines.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] It has been described as "six welding lasers strapped together." A 60 kW system, HELIOS, is being developed for destroyer-class ships as of 2020.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Lasers can be used as incapacitating non-lethal weapons.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] They can cause temporary or permanent vision loss when directed at the eyes.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Even lasers with a power output of less than one watt can cause immediate and permanent vision loss under certain conditions, making them potentially non-lethal but incapacitating weapons.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The use of such lasers is morally controversial due to the extreme handicap that laser-induced blindness represents.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The Protocol on Blinding Laser Weapons bans the use of weapons designed to cause permanent blindness.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Weapons designed to cause temporary blindness, known as dazzlers, are used by military and sometimes law enforcement organizations.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] In recent years, some hobbyists have taken an interest in lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Lasers used by hobbyists are generally of class IIIa or IIIb , although some have made their own class IV types.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] However, due to the cost and potential dangers, this is an uncommon hobby.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Some hobbyists salvage laser diodes from broken DVD players (red), Blu-ray players (violet), or even higher power laser diodes from CD or DVD burners.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Hobbyists have also used surplus lasers taken from retired military applications and modified them for holography.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Pulsed ruby and YAG lasers work well for this application.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Different applications need lasers with different output powers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Lasers that produce a continuous beam or a series of short pulses can be compared on the basis of their average power.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Lasers that produce pulses can also be characterized based on the *peak* power of each pulse.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The peak power of a pulsed laser is many orders of magnitude greater than its average power.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The average output power is always less than the power consumed.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Left: European laser warning symbol required for Class 2 lasers and higher.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Even the first laser was recognized as being potentially dangerous.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Theodore Maiman characterized the first laser as having the power of one "Gillette", as it could burn through one Gillette razor blade.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Today, it is accepted that even low-power lasers with only a few milliwatts of output power can be hazardous to human eyesight when the beam hits the eye directly or after reflection from a shiny surface.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] At wavelengths which the cornea and the lens can focus well, the coherence and low divergence of laser light means that it can be focused by the eye into an extremely small spot on the retina, resulting in localized burning and permanent damage in seconds or even less time.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The indicated powers are for visible-light, continuous-wave lasers.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] For pulsed lasers and invisible wavelengths, other power limits apply.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] People working with class 3B and class 4 lasers can protect their eyes with safety goggles which are designed to absorb light of a particular wavelength.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Infrared lasers with wavelengths longer than about 1.4 micrometers are often referred to as "eye-safe", because the cornea tends to absorb light at these wavelengths, protecting the retina from damage.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] The label "eye-safe" can be misleading, however, as it applies only to relatively low-power continuous wave beams; a high-power or Q-switched laser at these wavelengths can burn the cornea, causing severe eye damage, and even moderate-power lasers can injure the eye.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Lasers can be a hazard to both civil and military aviation, due to the potential to temporarily distract or blind pilots.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] See Lasers and aviation safety for more on this topic.
[src:laser-physics/laser-p02] Cameras based on charge-coupled devices may be more sensitive to laser damage than biological eyes.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Although laser light is perhaps the purest form of light, it is not of a single, pure frequency or wavelength.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] All lasers produce light over some natural bandwidth or range of frequencies.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] A laser's bandwidth of operation is determined primarily by the gain medium from which the laser is constructed, and the range of frequencies over which a laser may operate is known as the gain bandwidth.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] For example, a typical helium–neon laser has a gain bandwidth of about 1.5 GHz (a wavelength range of about 0.002 nm at a central wavelength of 633 nm), whereas a titanium-doped sapphire (Ti:sapphire) solid-state laser has a bandwidth of about 128 THz (a 300 nm wavelength range centered at 800 nm).
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The second factor to determine a laser's emission frequencies is the optical cavity (or resonant cavity) of the laser.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In the simplest case, this consists of two plane (flat) mirrors facing each other, surrounding the gain medium of the laser (this arrangement is known as a Fabry–Pérot cavity).
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Since light is a wave, when bouncing between the mirrors of the cavity, the light constructively and destructively interferes with itself, leading to the formation of standing waves, or modes, between the mirrors.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] These standing waves form a discrete set of frequencies, known as the *longitudinal modes* of the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] These modes are the only frequencies of light that are self-regenerating and allowed to oscillate by the resonant cavity; all other frequencies of light are suppressed by destructive interference.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] For a simple plane-mirror cavity, the allowed modes are those for which the separation distance of the mirrors L is an exact multiple of half the wavelength of the light λ, such that *L* = *qλ* / 2, where q is an integer known as the mode order.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In practice, L is usually much greater than λ, so the relevant values of *q* are large (around 105 to 106).
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Of more interest is the frequency separation between any two adjacent modes *q* and *q* + 1; this is given (for an empty linear resonator of length *L*) by Δ*ν* = *c* / 2*L*, where c is the speed of light (≈ 3×108 m/s).
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Using the above equation, a small laser with a mirror separation of 30 cm has a frequency separation between longitudinal modes of 0.5 GHz.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Thus for the two lasers referenced above, with a 30 cm cavity, the 1.5 GHz bandwidth of the HeNe laser would support up to 3 longitudinal modes, whereas the 128 THz bandwidth of the Ti:sapphire laser could support approximately 250,000 modes.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] When more than one longitudinal mode is excited, the laser is said to be in "multi-mode" operation.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] When only one longitudinal mode is excited, the laser is said to be in "single-mode" operation.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Each individual longitudinal mode has some bandwidth or narrow range of frequencies over which it operates, but typically this bandwidth, determined by the *Q* factor of the cavity (see Fabry–Pérot interferometer), is much smaller than the intermode frequency separation.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In a simple laser, each of these modes oscillates independently, with no fixed relationship between each other, in essence like a set of independent lasers, all emitting light at slightly different frequencies.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The individual phase of the light waves in each mode is not fixed and may vary randomly due to such things as thermal changes in materials of the laser.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In lasers with only a few oscillating modes, interference between the modes can cause beating effects in the laser output, leading to fluctuations in intensity; in lasers with many thousands of modes, these interference effects tend to average to a near-constant output intensity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] If instead of oscillating independently, each mode operates with a fixed phase between it and the other modes, then the laser output behaves quite differently.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Instead of a random or constant output intensity, the modes of the laser will periodically all constructively interfere with one another, producing an intense burst or pulse of light.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Such a laser is said to be "mode-locked" or "phase-locked".
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] These pulses occur separated in time by *τ* = 2*L*/*c*, where τ is the time taken for the light to make exactly one round trip of the laser cavity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] This time corresponds to a frequency exactly equal to the mode spacing of the laser, Δ*ν* = 1/*τ*.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The duration of each pulse of light is determined by the number of modes oscillating in phase (in a real laser, it is not necessarily true that all of the laser's modes are phase-locked).
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] If there are N modes locked with a frequency separation Δ*ν*, then the overall mode-locked bandwidth is *N*Δ*ν*, and the wider this bandwidth, the shorter the pulse duration from the laser.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In practice, the actual pulse duration is determined by the shape of each pulse, which is in turn determined by the exact amplitude and phase relationship of each longitudinal mode.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The value 0.441 is known as the "time–bandwidth product" of the pulse and varies depending on the pulse shape.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] For ultrashort-pulse lasers, a hyperbolic-secant-squared (sech2) pulse shape is often assumed, giving a time–bandwidth product of 0.315.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Using this equation, the minimum pulse duration can be calculated consistent with the measured laser spectral width.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] For the HeNe laser with a 1.5 GHz bandwidth, the shortest Gaussian pulse consistent with this spectral width is around 300 picoseconds; for the 128 THz bandwidth Ti:sapphire laser, this spectral width corresponds to a pulse of only 3.4 femtoseconds.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] These values represent the shortest possible Gaussian pulses consistent with the laser's bandwidth; in a real mode-locked laser, the actual pulse duration depends on many other factors, such as the actual pulse shape and the overall dispersion of the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Subsequent modulation could, in principle, shorten the pulse width of such a laser further; however, the measured spectral width would then be correspondingly increased.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] There are many ways to lock frequency, but the basic principle is the same, which is based on the feedback loop of the laser system.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The starting point of the feedback loop is the quantity that must be stabilized (frequency or phase).
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] To check whether frequency changes with time, a reference is needed.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] A common way to measure laser frequency is to link it with a geometrical property of an optical cavity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The Fabry-Pérot cavity is most commonly used for this purpose, consisting of two parallel mirrors separated by some distance.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] This method is based on the fact that light can resonate and be transmitted only if the optical path length of a single round trip is an integer multiple of the wavelength of the light.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Deviation of a laser's frequency from this condition will decrease transmission of that frequency.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Therefore, to obtain a small cavity line width, mirrors must have higher reflectivity, so to reduce the line width of the laser to the lowest extent, a high finesse cavity is required.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Methods for producing mode locking in a laser may be classified as either "active" or "passive".
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Active methods typically involve using an external signal to induce a modulation of the intracavity light.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Passive methods do not use an external signal, but rely on placing some element into the laser cavity which causes self-modulation of the light.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The most common active mode-locking technique places a standing wave electro-optic modulator into the laser cavity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] When driven with an electrical signal, this produces a sinusoidal amplitude modulation of the light in the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Considering this in the frequency domain, if a mode has optical frequency ν and is amplitude-modulated at a frequency f, then the resulting signal has sidebands at optical frequencies *ν* − *f* and *ν* + *f*.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] If the modulator is driven at the same frequency as the cavity mode spacing Δ*ν*, then these sidebands correspond to the two cavity modes adjacent to the original mode.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Since the sidebands are driven in-phase, the central mode and the adjacent modes will be phase-locked together.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Further operation of the modulator on the sidebands produces phase locking of the *ν* − 2*f* and *ν* + 2*f* modes, and so on until all modes in the gain bandwidth are locked.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] As said above, typical lasers are multi-mode and not seeded by a root mode, so multiple modes need to work out which phase to use.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In a passive cavity with this locking applied, there is no way to dump the entropy given by the original independent phases.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] This locking is better described as a coupling, leading to a complicated behavior and not clean pulses.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The coupling is only dissipative because of the dissipative nature of the amplitude modulation; otherwise, the phase modulation would not work.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] This process can also be considered in the time domain.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The amplitude modulator acts as a weak "shutter" to the light bouncing between the mirrors of the cavity, attenuating the light when it is "closed" and letting it through when it is "open".
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] If the modulation rate f is synchronised to the cavity round-trip time τ, then a single pulse of light will bounce back and forth in the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The actual strength of the modulation does not have to be large; a modulator that attenuates 1% of the light when "closed" will mode-lock a laser, since the same part of the light is repeatedly attenuated as it traverses the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Related to this amplitude modulation (AM), active mode locking is frequency-modulation (FM) mode locking, which uses a modulator device based on the acousto-optic effect.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] This device, when placed in a laser cavity and driven with an electrical signal, induces a small, sinusoidally varying frequency shift in the light passing through it.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] If the frequency of modulation is matched to the round-trip time of the cavity, then some light in the cavity sees repeated upshifts in frequency, and some repeated downshifts.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] After many repetitions, the upshifted and downshifted light is swept out of the gain bandwidth of the laser.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The only light unaffected is that which passes through the modulator when the induced frequency shift is zero, which forms a narrow pulse of light.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The third method of active mode locking is synchronous mode locking, or synchronous pumping.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In this, the pump source (energy source) for the laser is itself modulated, effectively turning the laser on and off to produce pulses.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Typically, the pump source is itself another mode-locked laser.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] This technique requires accurately matching the cavity lengths of the pump laser and the driven laser.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Passive mode-locking techniques are those that do not require a signal external to the laser (such as the driving signal of a modulator) to produce pulses.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Rather, they use the light in the cavity to cause a change in some intracavity element, which will then itself produce a change in the intracavity light.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] A commonly used device to achieve this is a saturable absorber.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] A saturable absorber is an optical device that exhibits an intensity-dependent transmission, meaning that the device behaves differently depending on the intensity of the light passing through it.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] For passive mode locking, ideally a saturable absorber selectively absorbs low-intensity light, but transmits light of sufficiently high intensity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] When placed in a laser cavity, a saturable absorber attenuates low-intensity constant-wave light (pulse wings).
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] However, because of the somewhat random intensity fluctuations experienced by an un-mode-locked laser, any random, intense spike is transmitted preferentially by the saturable absorber.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] As the light in the cavity oscillates, this process repeats, leading to the selective amplification of the high-intensity spikes and the absorption of the low-intensity light.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] After many round trips, this leads to a train of pulses and mode locking of the laser.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Saturable absorbers are commonly liquid organic dyes, but they can also be made from doped crystals and semiconductors.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Semiconductor absorbers tend to exhibit very fast response times (~100 fs), which is one of the factors that determines the final duration of the pulses in a passively mode-locked laser.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In a *colliding-pulse mode-locked laser* the absorber steepens the leading edge, while the lasing medium steepens the trailing edge of the pulse.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] There are also passive mode-locking schemes that do not rely on materials that directly display an intensity-dependent absorption.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In these methods, nonlinear optical effects in intracavity components are used to provide a method of selectively amplifying high-intensity light in the cavity and attenuation of low-intensity light.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] One of the most successful schemes is called Kerr-lens mode locking (KLM), also sometimes called "self-mode-locking".
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] This uses a nonlinear optical process, the optical Kerr effect, which results in high-intensity light being focused differently from low-intensity light.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] By careful arrangement of an aperture in the laser cavity, this effect can be exploited to produce the equivalent of an ultra-fast response-time saturable absorber.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In some semiconductor lasers, a combination of the two above techniques can be used.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Using a laser with a saturable absorber and modulating the electrical injection at the same frequency the laser is locked at, the laser can be stabilized by the electrical injection.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] This has the advantage of stabilizing the phase noise of the laser and can reduce the timing jitter of the pulses from the laser.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Coherent phase-information transfer between subsequent laser pulses has also been observed from nanowire lasers.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Here, the phase information has been stored in the residual photon field of coherent Rabi oscillations in the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Such findings open the way to phase locking of light sources integrated onto chip-scale photonic circuits and applications, such as on-chip Ramsey comb spectroscopy.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Fourier-domain mode locking (FDML) is a laser mode-locking technique that creates a continuous-wave, wavelength-swept light output.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] A main application for FDML lasers is optical coherence tomography.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] In practice, a number of design considerations affect the performance of a mode-locked laser.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The most important are the overall dispersion of the laser's optical resonator, which can be controlled with a prism compressor or some dispersive mirrors placed in the cavity, and optical nonlinearities.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] For excessive net group delay dispersion (GDD) of the laser cavity, the phase of the cavity modes can not be locked over a large bandwidth, and it will be difficult to obtain very short pulses.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] For a suitable combination of negative (anomalous) net GDD with the Kerr nonlinearity, soliton-like interactions may stabilize the mode locking and help to generate shorter pulses.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The shortest possible pulse duration is usually accomplished either for zero dispersion (without nonlinearities) or for some slightly negative (anomalous) dispersion (exploiting the soliton mechanism).
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The shortest directly produced optical pulses are generally produced by Kerr-lens mode-locked Ti:sapphire lasers and are around 5 femtoseconds long.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Alternatively, amplified pulses of a similar duration are created through the compression of longer (e.g.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] 30 fs) pulses by self-phase modulation in a hollow-core fibre or during filamentation.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] However, the minimum pulse duration is limited by the period of the carrier frequency (which is about 2.7 fs for Ti:sapphire systems); therefore, shorter pulses require moving to shorter wavelengths.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Some advanced techniques (involving high-harmonic generation with amplified femtosecond laser pulses) can be used to produce optical features with durations as short as 100 attoseconds in the extreme ultraviolet spectral region (i.e. <30 nm).
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Monochromatic light is the property of the laser depends on the fundamental working principle of the laser which contains frequency-selective elements.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] For example, in diode lasers, external mirror resonators and gratings are those elements.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] With the help of these elements, frequency selection leads to a very narrow spectral emission of light.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] However, when observed closely, there are frequency fluctuations that occur on different time scales.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] There can be different reasons for their origin, such as fluctuation in input voltage, acoustic vibration, or change in pressure and temperature of the surroundings.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] So, to narrow down these frequency fluctuations, it is necessary to stabilize the phase or frequency of the laser to an external extent.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Stabilizing laser properties using any external source or external reference is generally called "laser locking" or simply "locking".
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The reason for generation to create error signals is to create an electronic signal which is proportional to the laser's deviation from a particular set frequency or phase, which is called a "lock point".
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] If the laser frequency is large, then the signal is positive; if frequency is very small, then the signal is negative.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The point where the signal is zero is called a lock point.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] Laser locking based on an error signal which is a function of frequency is called frequency locking and if the error signal is a function of phase deviation of laser then this locking is referred to as phase locking.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] If the signal is created using an optical setup involving references like frequency references, then by using the reference, the optical signal is directly converted into frequencies which can be detected directly.
[src:laser-physics/mode-locking] The other way is to record the signal using a photodiode or camera and further change this signal electronically.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] An **optical cavity**, **resonating cavity** or **optical resonator** is an arrangement of mirrors or other optical elements that confines light waves similarly to how a cavity resonator confines microwaves.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Optical cavities are a major component of lasers, surrounding the gain medium and providing feedback of the laser light.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] They are also used in optical parametric oscillators and some interferometers.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Light confined in the cavity reflects multiple times, producing modes with certain resonance frequencies.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Modes can be decomposed into longitudinal modes that differ only in frequency and transverse modes that have different intensity patterns across the cross section of the beam.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Many types of optical cavities produce standing wave modes.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Different resonator types are distinguished by the focal lengths of the two mirrors and the distance between them.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Flat mirrors are not often used because of the difficulty of aligning them to the needed precision.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] The geometry (resonator type) must be chosen so that the beam remains stable, i.e. the size of the beam does not continually grow with multiple reflections.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Resonator types are also designed to meet other criteria such as a minimum beam waist or having no focal point (and therefore no intense light at a single point) inside the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Optical cavities are designed to have a large Q factor, meaning a beam undergoes many oscillation cycles with little attenuation.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] In the regime of high Q values, this is equivalent to the frequency line width being small compared to the resonant frequency of the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Light confined in a resonator will reflect multiple times from the mirrors, and due to the effects of interference, only certain patterns and frequencies of radiation will be sustained by the resonator, with the others being suppressed by destructive interference.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] In general, radiation patterns which are reproduced on every round-trip of the light through the resonator are the most stable.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] These are known as the *modes* of the resonator.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Resonator modes can be divided into two types: longitudinal modes, which differ in frequency from each other; and transverse modes, which may differ in both frequency and the intensity pattern of the light.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] The basic, or fundamental transverse mode of a resonator is a Gaussian beam.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] The most common types of optical cavities consist of two facing plane (flat) or spherical mirrors.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] The simplest of these is the plane-parallel or Fabry–Pérot cavity, consisting of two opposing flat mirrors.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] While simple, this arrangement is rarely used in large-scale lasers due to the difficulty of alignment; the mirrors must be aligned parallel within a few seconds of arc, or "walkoff" of the intracavity beam will result in it spilling out of the sides of the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] However, this problem is much reduced for very short cavities with a small mirror separation distance (*L* < 1 cm).
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Plane-parallel resonators are therefore commonly used in microchip and microcavity lasers and semiconductor lasers.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] In these cases, rather than using separate mirrors, a reflective optical coating may be directly applied to the laser medium itself.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] The plane-parallel resonator is also the basis of the Fabry–Pérot interferometer.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] For a resonator with two mirrors with radii of curvature *R*1 and *R*2, there are a number of common cavity configurations.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] If the two radii are equal to half the cavity length (*R*1 = *R*2 = *L* / 2), a concentric or spherical resonator results.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] This type of cavity produces a diffraction-limited beam waist in the centre of the cavity, with large beam diameters at the mirrors, filling the whole mirror aperture.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Similar to this is the hemispherical cavity, with one plane mirror and one mirror of radius equal to the cavity length.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] A common and important design is the confocal resonator, with mirrors of equal radii to the cavity length (*R*1 = *R*2 = *L*).
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] This design produces the smallest possible beam diameter at the cavity mirrors for a given cavity length, and is often used in lasers where the purity of the transverse mode pattern is important.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] A concave-convex cavity has one convex mirror with a negative radius of curvature.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] This design produces no intracavity focus of the beam, and is thus useful in very high-power lasers where the intensity of the light might be damaging to the intracavity medium if brought to a focus.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Less common resonator types include optical ring resonators and whispering-gallery mode resonators, in which a resonance is formed by waves moving in a closed loop rather than reflecting between two mirrors.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Only certain ranges of values for *R*1, *R*2, and *L* produce stable resonators in which periodic refocussing of the intracavity beam is produced.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] If the cavity is unstable, the beam size will grow without limit, eventually growing larger than the size of the cavity mirrors and being lost.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Values which satisfy the inequality correspond to stable resonators.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] and plotting *g*1 against *g*2 as shown.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Areas bounded by the line *g*1 *g*2 = 1 and the axes are stable.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Cavities at points exactly on the line are marginally stable; small variations in cavity length can cause the resonator to become unstable, and so lasers using these cavities are in practice often operated just inside the stability line.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] A simple geometric statement describes the regions of stability: A cavity is stable if the line segments between the mirrors and their centers of curvature overlap, but one does not lie entirely within the other.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] In the confocal cavity, if a ray is deviated from its original direction in the middle of the cavity, its displacement after reflecting from one of the mirrors is larger than in any other cavity design.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] This prevents amplified spontaneous emission and is important for designing high power amplifiers with good beam quality.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] If the optical cavity is not empty (e.g., a laser cavity which contains the gain medium), the value of *L* needs to be adjusted to account for the index of refraction of the medium.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Optical elements such as lenses placed in the cavity alter the stability and mode size.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] In addition, for most gain media, thermal and other inhomogeneities create a variable lensing effect in the medium, which must be considered in the design of the laser resonator.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Practical laser resonators may contain more than two mirrors; three- and four-mirror arrangements are common, producing a "folded cavity".
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Commonly, a pair of curved mirrors form one or more confocal sections, with the rest of the cavity being quasi-collimated and using plane mirrors.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] The shape of the laser beam depends on the type of resonator: The beam produced by stable, paraxial resonators can be well modeled by a Gaussian beam.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] In special cases the beam can be described as a single transverse mode and the spatial properties can be well described by the Gaussian beam, itself.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] More generally, this beam may be described as a superposition of transverse modes.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Accurate description of such a beam involves expansion over some complete, orthogonal set of functions (over two-dimensions) such as Hermite polynomials or the Ince polynomials.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Unstable laser resonators on the other hand, have been shown to produce fractal shaped beams.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Some intracavity elements are usually placed at a beam waist between folded sections.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Examples include acousto-optic modulators for cavity dumping and vacuum spatial filters for transverse mode control.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] For some low power lasers, the laser gain medium itself may be positioned at a beam waist.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Other elements, such as filters, prisms and diffraction gratings often need large quasi-collimated beams.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] These designs allow compensation of the cavity beam's astigmatism, which is produced by Brewster-cut elements in the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] A Z-shaped arrangement of the cavity also compensates for coma while the 'delta' or X-shaped cavity does not.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Out of plane resonators lead to rotation of the beam profile and more stability.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] The heat generated in the gain medium leads to frequency drift of the cavity, therefore the frequency can be actively stabilized by locking it to unpowered cavity.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Similarly the pointing stability of a laser may still be improved by spatial filtering by an optical fibre.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Precise alignment is important when assembling an optical cavity.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] For best output power and beam quality, optical elements must be aligned such that the path followed by the beam is centered through each element.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Simple cavities are often aligned with an alignment laser—a well-collimated visible laser that can be directed along the axis of the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Observation of the path of the beam and its reflections from various optical elements allows the elements' positions and tilts to be adjusted.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] More complex cavities may be aligned using devices such as electronic autocollimators and laser beam profilers.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] Optical cavities can also be used as multipass optical delay lines, folding a light beam so that a long path-length may be achieved in a small space.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] A plane-parallel cavity with flat mirrors produces a flat zigzag light path, but as discussed above, these designs are very sensitive to mechanical disturbances and walk-off.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] When curved mirrors are used in a nearly confocal configuration, the beam travels on a circular zigzag path.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] The latter is called a Herriott-type delay line.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] A fixed insertion mirror is placed off-axis near one of the curved mirrors, and a mobile pickup mirror is similarly placed near the other curved mirror.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] A flat linear stage with one pickup mirror is used in case of flat mirrors and a rotational stage with two mirrors is used for the Herriott-type delay line.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] The rotation of the beam inside the cavity alters the polarization state of the beam.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] To compensate for this, a single pass delay line is also needed, made of either a three or two mirrors in a 3d respective 2d retro-reflection configuration on top of a linear stage.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] To adjust for beam divergence a second car on the linear stage with two lenses can be used.
[src:laser-physics/optical-cavity] The two lenses act as a telescope producing a flat phase front of a Gaussian beam on a virtual end mirror.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In physics, specifically statistical mechanics, a **population inversion** occurs when a system (such as a group of atoms or molecules) exists in a state in which more members of the system are in higher, excited states than in lower, unexcited energy states.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] It is called an "inversion" because in many familiar and commonly encountered physical systems in thermal equilibrium, this is not possible.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] This concept is of fundamental importance in laser science because the production of a population inversion is a necessary step in the workings of a standard laser.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] To understand the concept of a population inversion, it is necessary to understand some thermodynamics and the way that light interacts with matter.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] To do so, it is useful to consider a very simple assembly of atoms forming a laser medium.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The *excited state*, with energy *E*2, with *E*2 > *E*1.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The number of these atoms which are in the ground state is given by *N*1, and the number in the excited state *N*2.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Calculable is the ratio of the populations of the two states at room temperature (T ≈ 300 K) for an energy difference Δ*E* that corresponds to light of a frequency corresponding to visible light (ν ≈ 5×1014 Hz).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Since *E*2 − *E*1 ≫ *kT*, it follows that the argument of the exponential in the equation above is a large negative number, and as such *N*2/*N*1 is vanishingly small; i.e., there are almost no atoms in the excited state.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] When in thermal equilibrium, then, it is seen that the lower energy state is more populated than the higher energy state, and this is the normal state of the system.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] As T increases, the number of electrons in the high-energy state (*N*2) increases, but *N*2 never exceeds *N*1 for a system at thermal equilibrium; rather, at infinite temperature, the populations *N*2 and *N*1 become equal.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In other words, a population inversion (*N*2/*N*1 > 1) can never exist for a system at thermal equilibrium.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] To achieve population inversion therefore requires pushing the system into a non-equilibrated state.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] If light (photons) of frequency *ν*12 passes through the group of atoms, there is a possibility of the light being absorbed by electrons which are in the ground state, which will cause them to be excited to the higher energy state.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The rate of absorption is proportional to the radiation density of the light, and also to the number of atoms currently in the ground state, *N*1.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] If atoms are in the excited state, spontaneous decay events to the ground state will occur at a rate proportional to *N*2, the number of atoms in the excited state.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The energy difference between the two states Δ*E*21 is emitted from the atom as a photon of frequency *ν*21 as given by the frequency-energy relation above.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The photons are emitted stochastically, and there is no fixed phase relationship between photons emitted from a group of excited atoms; in other words, spontaneous emission is incoherent.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In the absence of other processes, the number of atoms in the excited state at time t, is given by $N_{2}(t)=N_{2}(0)\exp {\frac {-t}{\tau _{21}}},$ where *N*2(0) is the number of excited atoms at time *t* = 0, and *τ*21 is the *mean lifetime* of the transition between the two states.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] If an atom is already in the excited state, it may be agitated by the passage of a photon that has a frequency *ν*21 corresponding to the energy gap Δ*E* of the excited state to ground state transition.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In this case, the excited atom relaxes to the ground state, and it produces a second photon of frequency *ν*21.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The original photon is not absorbed by the atom, and so the result is two photons of the same frequency.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] This process is known as *stimulated emission*.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Specifically, an excited atom will act like a small electric dipole which will oscillate with the external field provided.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] One of the consequences of this oscillation is that it encourages electrons to decay to the lowest energy state.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] When this happens due to the presence of the electromagnetic field from a photon, a photon is released in the same phase and direction as the "stimulating" photon, and is called stimulated emission.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The rate at which stimulated emission occurs is proportional to the number of atoms *N*2 in the excited state, and the radiation density of the light.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The base probability of a photon causing stimulated emission in a single excited atom was shown by Albert Einstein to be exactly equal to the probability of a photon being absorbed by an atom in the ground state.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Therefore, when the numbers of atoms in the ground and excited states are equal, the rate of stimulated emission is equal to the rate of absorption for a given radiation density.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The critical detail of stimulated emission is that the induced photon has the same frequency and phase as the incident photon.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In other words, the two photons are coherent.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] It is this property that allows optical amplification, and the production of a laser system.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] During the operation of a laser, all three light–matter interactions described above are taking place.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Initially, atoms are energized from the ground state to the excited state by a process called *pumping*, described below.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Some of these atoms decay via spontaneous emission, releasing incoherent light as photons of frequency, ν.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] These photons are fed back into the laser medium, usually by an optical resonator.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Some of these photons are absorbed by the atoms in the ground state, and the photons are lost to the laser process.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] However, some photons cause stimulated emission in excited-state atoms, releasing another coherent photon.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In effect, this results in *optical amplification*.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] If the number of photons being amplified per unit time is greater than the number of photons being absorbed, then the net result is a continuously increasing number of photons being produced; the laser medium is said to have a gain of greater than unity.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Recall from the descriptions of absorption and stimulated emission above that the rates of these two processes are proportional to the number of atoms in the ground and excited states, *N*1 and *N*2, respectively.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] If the ground state has a higher population than the excited state (*N*1 > *N*2), then the absorption process dominates, and there is a net attenuation of photons.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] If the populations of the two states are the same (*N*1 = *N*2), the rate of absorption of light exactly balances the rate of emission; the medium is then said to be *optically transparent*.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] If the higher energy state has a greater population than the lower energy state (*N*1 < *N*2), then the emission process dominates, and light in the system undergoes a net increase in intensity.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] It is thus clear that to produce a faster rate of stimulated emissions than absorptions, it is required that the ratio of the populations of the two states is such that *N*2/*N*1 > 1; In other words, a population inversion is required for laser operation.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Many transitions involving electromagnetic radiation are strictly forbidden under quantum mechanics.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The allowed transitions are described by so-called selection rules, which describe the conditions under which a radiative transition is allowed.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] For instance, transitions are only allowed if Δ*S* = 0, S being the total spin angular momentum of the system.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In real materials, other effects, such as interactions with the crystal lattice, intervene to circumvent the formal rules by providing alternate mechanisms.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In these systems, the forbidden transitions can occur, but usually at slower rates than allowed transitions.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] A classic example is phosphorescence where a material has a ground state with *S* = 0, an excited state with *S* = 0, and an intermediate state with *S* = 1.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The transition from the intermediate state to the ground state by emission of light is slow because of the selection rules.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Thus emission may continue after the external illumination is removed.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In contrast fluorescence in materials is characterized by emission which ceases when the external illumination is removed.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Transitions that do not involve the absorption or emission of radiation are not affected by selection rules.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The radiationless transition between levels, such as between the excited *S* = 0 and *S* = 1 states, may proceed quickly enough to siphon off a portion of the *S* = 0 population before it spontaneously returns to the ground state.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The existence of intermediate states in materials is essential to the technique of optical pumping of lasers (see below).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] A population inversion is required for laser operation, but cannot be achieved in the above theoretical group of atoms with two energy-levels when they are in thermal equilibrium.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In fact, any method by which the atoms are directly and continuously excited from the ground state to the excited state (such as optical absorption) will eventually reach equilibrium with the de-exciting processes of spontaneous and stimulated emission.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] At best, an equal population of the two states, *N*1 = *N*2 = *N*/2, can be achieved, resulting in optical transparency but no net optical gain.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] To achieve lasting non-equilibrium conditions, an indirect method of populating the excited state must be used.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] A *three-level laser* may achieve population inversion.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] It consists of a group of N atoms, with each atom able to exist in any of three energy states, levels 1, 2 and 3, with energies *E*1, *E*2, and *E*3, and populations *N*1, *N*2, and *N*3, respectively.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] *E*1 < *E*2 < *E*3; that is, the energy of level 2 lies between that of level 1 and level 3.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The level 1 is also referred to as the *ground state*.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Initially, the system of atoms is at thermal equilibrium, and the majority of the atoms will be in the ground state, i.e., *N*1 ≈ *N*, *N*2 ≈ *N*3 ≈ 0.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The atoms can be excited from level 1 to level 3 and this act is called *pumping*.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] It can happen when the atoms are subjected to light of a frequency $\nu _{13}\,=\,{\frac {1}{h}}\left(E_{3}-E_{1}\right),$ the process of optical absorption will excite electrons from level 1 to level 3.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] There are also methods not directly involving light absorption; such as electrical discharge or chemical reactions.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The level 3 is sometimes referred to as the *pump level* or *pump band*, and the energy transition *E*1 → *E*3 as the *pump transition* (labeled transition **P** in the diagram on the right).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Upon pumping the medium, an appreciable number of atoms will transition to level 3, such that *N*3 > 0.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] To have a medium suitable for laser operation, it is necessary that these excited atoms quickly decay to level 2.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The energy released in this transition may be emitted as a photon (spontaneous emission).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] However, in practice, the 3 → 2 transition is usually *non-radiative* (labeled transition **R** in the diagram), with the energy being released as phonons and transferred to vibrational motion (heat) of the host material surrounding the atoms, without the generation of a photon.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] This phenomenon is sometimes called *collisional deactivation*.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] An electron in level 2 may decay by spontaneous emission to level 1, releasing a photon of frequency *ν*12 (given by *E*2 − *E*1 = *hν*12), which is called the *laser transition*s (labelled transition **L** in the diagram).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] If over half the *N* atoms can be accumulated in this state, this will exceed the population of the ground state *N*1.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] A population inversion (*N*2 > *N*1) has thus been achieved between level 1 and 2, and optical amplification at the frequency *ν*21 can be obtained.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Because at least half the population of atoms must be excited from the ground state to obtain a population inversion, the laser medium must be very strongly pumped.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] This makes three-level lasers rather inefficient, despite being the first type of laser to be discovered (based on a ruby laser medium, by Theodore Maiman in 1960).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] A three-level system could also have a radiative transition between level 3 and 2, and a non-radiative transition between 2 and 1.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In this case, the pumping requirements are weaker.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In practice, most lasers are *four-level lasers*, described below.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In a *four-level laser,* there are four energy levels, levels 1, 2, 3, 4, with energies *E*1, *E*2, *E*3, *E*4, and populations *N*1, *N*2, *N*3, *N*4, respectively.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The energies of each level are such that *E*1 < *E*2 < *E*3 < *E*4.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In this system, the pumping transition **P** excites the atoms from level 1 to level 4 (the pump level).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] From level 4, the atoms decay by a fast, non-radiative transition **Ra** into the level 3.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Since the lifetime of the laser transition **L** is long compared to that of **Ra** (*τ*32 ≫ *τ*43), a population accumulates in level 3 (the *upper laser level*), which may relax by spontaneous or stimulated emission into level 2 (the *lower laser level*).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] This level likewise has a fast, non-radiative decay **Rb** into level 1.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] As in three-level laser, the presence of a fast, non-radiative decay transition results in the population of the pump band being quickly depleted (*N*4 ≈ 0).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In a four-level system, any atom in level 2 (the lower laser level) is also quickly de-excited, leading to a negligible population in that state (*N*2 ≈ 0).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] This is important, since any appreciable population accumulating in level 3 (the upper laser level) will form a population inversion with respect to level 2.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] That is, as long as *N*3 > 0, then *N*3 > *N*2, and a population inversion is achieved.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Thus optical amplification, and laser operation, can take place at a frequency of *ν*32 (*E*3 − *E*2 = *hν*32).
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Since only a few atoms must be excited into the upper laser level to form a population inversion (*N*2 ≈ 0 and *N*3 > 0, then *N*3 > *N*2 which means inversion), a four-level laser is much more efficient than a three-level one, and most practical lasers are of this type.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In reality, many more than four energy levels may be involved in the laser process, with complex excitation and relaxation processes involved between these levels.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In particular, the pump band may consist of several distinct energy levels, or a continuum of levels, which allow optical pumping of the medium over a wide range of wavelengths.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Note that in both three- and four-level lasers, the energy of the pumping transition is greater than that of the laser transition.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] This means that, if the laser is optically pumped, the frequency of the pumping light must be greater than that of the resulting laser light.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In other words, the pump wavelength is shorter than the laser wavelength.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] It is possible in some media to use multiple photon absorptions between multiple lower-energy transitions to reach the pump level; such lasers are called *up-conversion* lasers.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] While in many lasers the laser process involves the transition of atoms between different electronic energy states, as described in the model above, this is not the only mechanism that can result in laser action.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] For example, there are many common lasers (e.g., dye lasers, carbon dioxide lasers) where the laser medium consists of complete molecules, and energy states correspond to vibrational and rotational modes of oscillation of the molecules.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] This is the case with water masers, that occur in nature.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In some media it is possible, by imposing an additional optical or microwave field, to use quantum coherence effects to reduce the likelihood of a ground-state to excited-state transition.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] This technique, known as lasing without inversion, allows optical amplification to take place without producing a population inversion between the two states.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] Stimulated emission was first observed in the microwave region of the electromagnetic spectrum, giving rise to the acronym MASER for Microwave Amplification by Stimulated Emission of Radiation.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] In the microwave region, the Boltzmann distribution of molecules among energy states is such that, at room temperature, all states are populated almost equally.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] To create a population inversion under these conditions, it is necessary to selectively remove some atoms or molecules from the system based on differences in properties.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] A strong inhomogeneous magnetic field will separate atoms in the higher energy state from a beam of mixed-state atoms.
[src:laser-physics/population-inversion] The separated population represents a population inversion that can exhibit stimulated emissions.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Q-switching was first proposed in 1958 by Gordon Gould, and independently discovered and demonstrated in 1961 or 1962 by Robert W.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] McClung at Hughes Research Laboratories using electrically switched Kerr cell shutters in a ruby laser.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Optical nonlinearities such as Q-switching were fully explained by Nicolaas Bloembergen, who won the Nobel Prize in 1981 for this work.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Q-switching is achieved by putting some type of variable attenuator inside the laser's optical resonator.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] When the attenuator is functioning, light which leaves the gain medium does not return, and lasing cannot begin.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] This attenuation inside the cavity corresponds to a decrease in the *Q factor* or *quality factor* of the optical resonator.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] A high Q factor corresponds to low resonator losses per roundtrip, and vice versa.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] The variable attenuator is commonly called a "Q-switch", when used for this purpose.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Initially the laser medium is pumped while the Q-switch is set to prevent feedback of light into the gain medium (producing an optical resonator with low Q).
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] This produces a population inversion, but laser operation cannot yet occur since there is no feedback from the resonator.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Since the rate of stimulated emission is dependent on the amount of light entering the medium, the amount of energy stored in the gain medium increases as the medium is pumped.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Due to losses from spontaneous emission and other processes, after a certain time the stored energy will reach some maximum level; the medium is said to be *gain saturated*.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] At this point, the Q-switch device is quickly changed from low to high Q, allowing feedback and the process of optical amplification by stimulated emission to begin.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Because of the large amount of energy already stored in the gain medium, the intensity of light in the laser resonator builds up very quickly; this also causes the energy stored in the medium to be depleted almost as quickly.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] The net result is a short pulse of light output from the laser, known as a *giant pulse*, which may have a very high peak intensity.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Here, the Q-switch is an externally controlled variable attenuator.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] This may be a mechanical device such as a shutter, chopper wheel, or spinning mirror/prism placed inside the cavity, or (more commonly) it may be some form of modulator such as an acousto–optic device, a magneto-optic effect device or an electro-optic device – a Pockels cell or Kerr cell.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] The reduction of losses (increase of Q) is triggered by an external event, typically an electrical signal.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] The pulse repetition rate can therefore be externally controlled.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Modulators generally allow a faster transition from low to high Q, and provide better control.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] An additional advantage of modulators is that the rejected light may be coupled out of the cavity and can be used for something else.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Alternatively, when the modulator is in its low-Q state, an externally generated beam can be coupled *into* the cavity through the modulator.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] This can be used to "seed" the cavity with a beam that has desired characteristics (such as transverse mode or wavelength).
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] When the Q is raised, lasing builds up from the initial seed, producing a Q-switched pulse that has characteristics inherited from the seed.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] In this case, the Q-switch is a saturable absorber, a material whose transmission increases when the intensity of light exceeds some threshold.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] The material may be an ion-doped crystal like Cr:YAG, which is used for Q-switching of Nd:YAG lasers, a bleachable dye, or a passive semiconductor device.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Initially, the loss of the absorber is high, but still low enough to permit some lasing once a large amount of energy is stored in the gain medium.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] As the laser power increases, it saturates the absorber, i.e., rapidly reduces the resonator loss, so that the power can increase even faster.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Ideally, this brings the absorber into a state with low losses to allow efficient extraction of the stored energy by the laser pulse.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] After the pulse, the absorber recovers to its high-loss state before the gain recovers, so that the next pulse is delayed until the energy in the gain medium is fully replenished.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] The pulse repetition rate can only indirectly be controlled, e.g. by varying the laser's pump power and the amount of saturable absorber in the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Direct control of the repetition rate can be achieved by using a pulsed pump source as well as passive Q-switching.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Jitter can be reduced by not reducing the Q by as much, so that a small amount of light can still circulate in the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] This provides a "seed" of light that can aid in the buildup of the next Q-switched pulse.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] With cavity dumping, the cavity end mirrors are 100% reflective, so that no output beam is produced when the Q is high.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Instead, the Q-switch is used to "dump" the beam out of the cavity after a time delay.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] The cavity Q goes from low to high to start the laser buildup, and then goes from high to low to "dump" the beam from the cavity all at once.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] This produces a shorter output pulse than regular Q-switching.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Electro-optic modulators are normally used for this, since they can easily be made to function as a near-perfect beam "switch" to couple the beam out of the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] The modulator that dumps the beam may be the same modulator that Q-switches the cavity, or a second (possibly identical) modulator.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] A dumped cavity is more complicated to align than simple Q-switching, and may need a control loop to choose the best time at which to dump the beam from the cavity.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] In regenerative amplification, an optical amplifier is placed inside a Q-switched cavity.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Pulses of light from another laser (the "master oscillator") are injected into the cavity by lowering the Q to allow the pulse to enter and then increasing the Q to confine the pulse to the cavity where it can be amplified by repeated passes through the gain medium.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] The pulse is then allowed to leave the cavity via another Q switch.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] A typical Q-switched laser (e.g. a Nd:YAG laser) with a resonator length of e.g.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] 10 cm can produce light pulses of several tens of nanoseconds duration.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Even when the average power is well below 1 W, the peak power can be many kilowatts.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Large-scale laser systems can produce Q-switched pulses with energies of many joules and peak powers in the gigawatt region.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Q-switched lasers are often used in applications which demand high laser intensities in nanosecond pulses, such as metal cutting or pulsed holography.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Nonlinear optics often takes advantage of the high peak powers of these lasers, offering applications such as 3D optical data storage and 3D microfabrication.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] However, Q-switched lasers can also be used for measurement purposes, such as for distance measurements (range finding) by measuring the time it takes for the pulse to get to some target and the reflected light to get back to the sender.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] It can be also used in chemical dynamic study, e.g. temperature jump relaxation study.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Q-switched lasers are also used to remove tattoos by shattering ink pigments into particles that are cleared by the body's lymphatic system.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Full removal can take between six and twenty treatments depending on the amount and colour of ink, spaced at least a month apart, using different wavelengths for different coloured inks.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Nd:YAG lasers are currently the most favoured lasers due to their high peak powers, high repetition rates and relatively low costs.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] In 2013 a picosecond laser was introduced based on clinical research which appears to show better clearance with difficult-to-remove colours such as green and light blue.
[src:laser-physics/q-switching] Q-switched lasers can also be used to remove dark spots and fix other skin pigmentation issues.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The phenomenon of stimulated emission was predicted by Albert Einstein in 1916, introducing what is now called the Einstein B Coefficient.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Einstein's work became the theoretical foundation of the maser and the laser.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The process is identical in form to atomic absorption in which the energy of an absorbed photon causes an identical but opposite atomic transition: from the lower level to a higher energy level.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Stimulated emission occurs when an atom in an excited state an interacts with an electromagnetic field.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] If the difference in energy between the excited state and a lower energy state matches the energy of occupied modes in the field, a photon can be emitted that matches the field photons in phase, energy, and polarization.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Stimulated emission requires an electromagnetic field.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The reverse process is absorption which consumes a photon from the field to raise the energy level of the atom, creating an excited state.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] In the absence of a field, the excited state will decay and emit a photon in a random process called "spontaneous emission".
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] This is the mechanism of fluorescence and thermal emission.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Stimulated emission was a theoretical discovery by Albert Einstein within the framework of the old quantum theory, wherein the emission is described in terms of photons that are the quanta of the EM field.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Einstein published a series of three papers on this topic.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The key work was his 1917 paper which introduced spontaneous and stimulated emission, as well as the Einstein coefficients.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Einstein's theory of radiation was ahead of its time and prefigures the modern theory of quantum electrodynamics and quantum optics by several decades.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Stimulated emission can be modelled mathematically by considering an atom that may be in one of two electronic energy states, a lower level state (possibly the ground state) (1) and an *excited state* (2), with energies *E*1 and *E*2 respectively.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] If the atom is in the excited state, it may decay into the lower state by the process of spontaneous emission, releasing the difference in energies between the two states as a photon.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The photon will have frequency *ν*0 and energy *hν*0, given by: $E_{2}-E_{1}=h\,\nu _{0}$ where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Alternatively, if the excited-state atom is perturbed by an electric field of frequency *ν*0, it may emit an additional photon of the same frequency and in phase, thus augmenting the external field, leaving the atom in the lower energy state.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] This process is known as stimulated emission.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The rate of emission is thus proportional to the number of atoms in the excited state *N*2, and to the density of incident photons.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] At the same time, there will be a process of atomic absorption which *removes* energy from the field while raising electrons from the lower state to the upper state.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Its rate is precisely the negative of the stimulated emission rate, ${\frac {\partial N_{2}}{\partial t}}=-{\frac {\partial N_{1}}{\partial t}}=B_{12}\,\rho (\nu )\,N_{1}.$ The rate of absorption is thus proportional to the number of atoms in the lower state, *N*1.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The B coefficients can be calculated using dipole approximation and time dependent perturbation theory in quantum mechanics as: $B_{ab}={\frac {e^{2}}{6\epsilon _{0}\hbar ^{2}}}|\langle a|{\vec {r}}|b\rangle |^{2}$ where *B* corresponds to energy distribution in terms of frequency *ν*.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The B coefficient may vary based on choice of energy distribution function used, however, the product of energy distribution function and its respective *B* coefficient remains same.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The notable characteristic of stimulated emission compared to everyday light sources (which depend on spontaneous emission) is that the emitted photons have the same frequency, phase, polarization, and direction of propagation as the incident photons.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The photons involved are thus mutually coherent.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The two photons are completely indistinguishable particles and can be considered "cloned biphotons".
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] When a population inversion ( $\Delta N>0$ ) is present, therefore, optical amplification of incident radiation will take place.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Although energy generated by stimulated emission is always at the exact frequency of the field which has stimulated it, the above rate equation refers only to excitation at the particular optical frequency $\nu _{0}$ corresponding to the energy of the transition.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] At frequencies offset from $\nu _{0}$ the strength of stimulated (or spontaneous) emission will be decreased according to the so-called line shape.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The peak value of the Lorentzian line shape occurs at the line center, $\nu =\nu _{0}$ .
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Thus stimulated emission at frequencies away from $\nu _{0}$ is reduced by this factor.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] In practice there may also be broadening of the line shape due to inhomogeneous broadening, most notably due to the Doppler effect resulting from the distribution of velocities in a gas at a certain temperature.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] This has a Gaussian shape and reduces the peak strength of the line shape function.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] In a practical problem the full line shape function can be computed through a convolution of the individual line shape functions involved.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Stimulated emission can also occur in classical models, without reference to photons or quantum-mechanics.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The classical electromagnetic field interacts with a classical medium and increases its energy (absorption) or decreases its energy (stimulated emission).
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Stimulated emission can provide a physical mechanism for optical amplification.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] If an external source of energy stimulates more than 50% of the atoms in the ground state to transition into the excited state, then what is called a population inversion is created.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] When light of the appropriate frequency passes through the inverted medium, the photons are either absorbed by the atoms that remain in the ground state or the photons stimulate the excited atoms to emit additional photons of the same frequency, phase, and direction.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] Since more atoms are in the excited state than in the ground state then an amplification of the input intensity results.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] where *g*1 and *g*2 are the degeneracies of energy levels 1 and 2, respectively.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] as long as the intensity *I*(*z*) is small enough so that it does not have a significant effect on the magnitude of the population inversion.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] is the *small-signal gain coefficient* (in units of radians per metre).
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] is the optical intensity of the input signal (in watts per square metre).
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The saturation intensity *I*S is defined as the input intensity at which the gain of the optical amplifier drops to exactly half of the small-signal gain.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] , which depends on the spontaneous emission lifetimes of the various transitions between the energy levels related to the amplification.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] The minimum value of $I_{\text{S}}(\nu )$ occurs on resonance, where the cross section $\sigma (\nu )$ is the largest.
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] For a simple two-level atom with a natural linewidth $\Gamma$ , the saturation time constant $\tau _{\text{S}}=\Gamma ^{-1}$ .
[src:laser-physics/stimulated-emission] which is identical to the small signal gain equation (see above).
